<HEAD>U.S. Delegation Nears Agreement on Compensation Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: retransmitting a0402 to eliminate garble at end</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have reached agreement in principle for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to pay compensation for the 37 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sailors killed aboard the frigate Stark in a May, 1987 Iraqi missile attack in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, sources said Monday. The compensation package still needs the formal approval of both governments, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. Progress on the stalled claim request was made when a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, led by <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> legal adviser <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON>, went to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> last week. The talks ended Monday and <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON> was headed back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. In their talks, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> teams apparently `` are reaching the final stages of achieving a substantial settlement on the claims,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. She said she did not know when the actual agreement would be concluded and could not divulge details of its content. At the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, defense sources said an agreement had been reached but they described the accord as `` tentative _ subject to review back here in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> presented <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> with a $ 29.6 million claim for the families of 37 crewmembers who died on the guided missile frigate Stark when an Iraqi jet fighter fired two French-made Exocet missiles at the ship. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> claimed the missile attack was a mistake born of the tensions of the Iran-Iraq war. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> claim was presented 11 months ago but <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> rejected the amount, which includes $ 800,000 for each of the families. The defense sources, who insisted on anonymity, said they could not discuss the dollar amount in the agreement or how it might be divided among the families of those who were killed; the sailors who were injured; and as settlement toward the cost of repairing the Stark. `` But apparently our negotiators are recommending we settle for a bit less than we were originally asking with the goal of ending further delays in settling the issue,'' one source said. In addition to the $ 29.6 million sought for the families of the 37 dead sailors, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has asked <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to pay $ 82.9 million to cover the cost of repairing the Stark and returning it to active duty with the fleet. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials have refused to say how much they asked <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to pay to sailors who suffered injuries but survived the attack.
