<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Outgoing baseball Commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> is discussing a purchase of strikebound <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> learned Monday. Meanwhile, a judge ordered a hearing on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s attempts to force its pilots back to work, and sources said former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is among those being considered to head the carrier's reorganization. An offer from <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> may be presented to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors within the next few days, airline industry and baseball sources said on condition of anonymity. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON>, contacted for comment at his <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> home, said, `` I've heard about it. But we just do n't comment on rumors.'' <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> said his company would have no comment on the matter. `` There are a lot of those rumors going around,'' <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> said. `` If and when any agreement is reached to sell Eastern I'm sure all the parties involved will issue a statement.'' <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, contacted in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said the commissioner did not wish to comment on the matter. A source said the deal would involve <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> businessman who is a friend of <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>'s and is majority owner of <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, who headed the host committee for the 1984 <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Olympics, is to step down as baseball commissioner on Saturday A call to <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON>'s office seeking comment Monday night was not answered. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s board is holding a regularly scheduled meeting Tuesday and Wednesday, said a source close to the company. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> was approached last fall by officials of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unions to consider taking over the troubled airline, which filed for bankruptcy protection March 9, five days after the start of the Machinists' strike supported by airline pilots The Machinists and pilots unions have said they would make concessions if <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> took over, possibly in return for ownership of part of the airline. A call to the Machinists local in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> was not answered Monday night. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> met with Eastern officials during baseball's winter meetings in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> last December, then traveled to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> for further talks, a baseball source said. In addition, <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> have discussed a possible buyout with <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> set a hearing Thursday on a key issue tossed back to him by an appeals court. The appellate court said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> must decide if the pilots are merely honoring <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union picket lines legally, or if they are trying to advance their own cause with their walkout, which could violate the National Railway Labor Act. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has backed the full hearing, denying their strike is illegal. In refusing to cross the picket line, <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> `` certainly considered our parallel interests to strengthen our position to obtain our own collective bargaining interests,'' said pilots' attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Linsey </PERSON> `` There is nothing wrong with that.'' Eastern proceeded on another front against the pilots Monday, inaugurating its first six-week training class to replace pilots who walked out with Machinists on March 4. While the carrier had planned to begin training up to 50 replacement pilots Monday, the class size ended up smaller than that. `` We cut back to 35,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON>, adding that all the new hires had impressive qualifications. The carrier said many are pilots from other carriers hoping to bump up their seniority by jumping to Eastern. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Trustee <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who is administering <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorginization in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said Monday he is considering about a dozen candidates for examiner in the complex case. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who declined to name names, said the ideal examiner would be `` someone who can play the role of statesman.'' Sources who spoke under condition of anonymity told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that the list includes <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and top securities fraud lawyer <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said he hopes to decide by late this week or early nex week, and will recommend that person to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Court Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> has said he would appoint an examiner with sweeping powers to try to mediate the bitter dispute between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and its unions. The examiner also will review financial transactions between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>, a Washington-based securities lawyer who represented some claimants in <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Chapter 11 proceeding starting in August 1982, also is one of the lead defense attorneys for imprisoned insider trader <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is now vice chairman and managing director of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carlyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, an investment banking firm in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> D.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s secretary said he was unavailable to comment. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> said he was n't aware he was on the list.
