<FIRST>r w PM-US-PhilippinesFarms     03-27 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Philippines Farms,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Third World Farmers Report Gains from Export Crops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When 448 farm households on the Philippine island of <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION> switched to raising sugar for sale to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, their earnings per acre grew to nearly double those of their neighbors. The cash crop brought the equivalent of just over $ 100 an acre in a year, compared with about $ 52 an acre for the corn grown by neighboring families. These were poor families, with farms that averaged only about 10 acres. In a country where the average citizen earns about $ 660 a year, the difference was huge. `` Contrary to conventional wisdom, farmers who produce crops for export have more income and are better fed than subsistence farmers who produce only basic food crops for home consumption,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, an independent study organization. The institute project was run by <PERSON> Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON>, a West Germam farm economist, with a grant from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> The study found at least one bad effect from the contracts offered by the <ORGANIZATION> Bukidnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>: some corn farmers sold their land or gave up leases and took jobs on sugar farms, creating a new group of landless farm workers. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> suggested that the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government should have gotten the mill to make contracts for sugar with the tenant farmers, as well as with those who owned land. The government could also have taken measures to improve the production of small farms that stayed with growing corn, making credit, fertilizer and new varieties available, he said. Contrary to some people's belief, the researchers saw no damage to child health _ but little improvement either _ from the change to cash crops. While better income from the sugar provided more food for the family, it did little to solve the problem of badly nourished children. Better health and sanitation measures are needed as well, the report said. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> said that as farmers' income rose, the proportion they spent on traditional foods went down. Spending on meat, housing, transport and education rose sharply among the most prosperous farmers in the Philippine group. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> studied farmers not only in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, but also in the east African republic of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> who made a similar switch, and Guatemalans who tried vegetables instead of corn. There were also groups in two more African countries who switched to farming for the market rather than for home consumption. In central African Rwanda they planted potatoes and tea instead of corn. In <LOCATION> Gambia </LOCATION>, on the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast, the shift was from swamp rice to peanuts and to rice under irrigation. The researchers found that when small farmers switched to cash crops, they often kept some of their land in traditional food crops as a kind of insurance. The study said that makes sense, because the income from cash crops is not always certain. Sugar prices have dropped from the levels that first made the switch attractive in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, for example.
</TEXT>
