<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Famine     03-27 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Famine,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Relief Effort Faces Daunting Problems in Sudan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20 of March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUGLAD, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Starvation and disease, abduction and slavery are some of the atrocities that six years of civil war have inflicted on millions of people of southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. Consider <PERSON> Akwa </PERSON> <PERSON> Karfath </PERSON> <PERSON> Kawal </PERSON>, a woman of <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> descent who fled hunger in her hometown of <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> and ended up in a squalid refugee area just outside <LOCATION> Muglad </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. Armed Arabs abducted her five sons en route, she says, forcing them into slavery as cattle herders. Another woman, <PERSON> Miriyal </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayowin </PERSON>, lost two toddlers to starvation and one to the Arabs during the trek out of the south. `` There is nothing in <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> but destruction and we were hungry, so we left,'' she said. `` We ate shrubs as we walked ... but there was no water. `` So many died.'' More than 12,000 refugees in this maze of huts made of sticks and plastic sheets tell similar tales. Dressed in rags, these Dinka tribesmen and their brethren in other camps have been changed by the war from cultivators and cattle breeders to paupers dependent on relief. The Dinka, largest of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s 115 tribes, form the backbone of the rebel army. They are Christians and animists. Rebels began fighting in 1983 for more autonomy from the government, which is dominated by the Moslem Arab majority in the north. On Sunday, a new broad-based Cabinet met for the first time in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> and endorsed a peace plan to end the war. And in April, the world will try to assuage the suffering of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s people with an ambitious emergency relief program coordinated by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. Relief workers for both Western donor governments and private organizations say the $ 132 million program will save the lives of some of the hundreds of thousands of southern Sudanese who face starvation. But they say the outside world has neglected the war and its ruin for so long that a logistical nightmare will further complicate the already precarious security situation. They doubt the logjams can be sufficiently overcome to prevent another disaster like last summer, when at least 250,000 people died after monsoon rains isolated them without food. Everyone agrees the need is real and urgent, even the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Though the rebels have refused a call by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> for a one-month truce to let the food pass, they have pledged not to attack supply convoys in certain protected corridors. The plan is to stockpile 100,000 tons of food, medicine and other supplies in places accessible to 2.25 million southerners in both government and rebel-held areas. The supplies are to be in place before the rainy season starts in May and paralyzes transportation. `` It's an enormous quantity and a short period of time,'' said one relief worker. `` Above all, this is <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>.'' Relief and government officials agreed to the plan for bringing in supplies by train, plane, <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barge and truck convoy. The government also promised to undo complicated bureaucratic procedures for the relief organizations. For their part, Western relief workers offer endless stories about bureaucratic inefficiency, generally on condition they not be identified. A British-based organization says it had to wait a year before four jeeps were cleared through Sudanese customs. A Dutch diplomat says he tried to transfer $ 4 million in aid to the emergency operation. He was handed forms to fill out and told that the transfer would probably take weeks. Much of the food must be transported to government-held southern areas on Nile barges or trains. However, the barges and trains have made no more than one trip in the past year because of security problems and nervous railway workers. The government says of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s 22 million people, 4 million are southerners. It says half have been displaced by the war to camps in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> or northern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, and half still need relief in the south. Southerners, however, claim they are 6 million. Western relief workers suspect that the discrepancy _ 2 million people _ represents the number who died as a result of the war.
</TEXT>
