<HEAD>For release 10 a.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Economy Faces Trouble Without Trade Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Improvements in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit will stall out next year without major policy changes on the part of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, posing grave economic dangers for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a research institute warned today. The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> issued a report forecasting that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trade deficit will begin rising again in 1990 and will hit $ 150 billion by 1992, very near the all-time record imbalance of $ 154 billion set in 1987. The projections are based on the current account, the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade. It includes not only trade in merchandise but also trade in services, primarily investment flows between countries. In 1988, the current account deficit narrowed to $ 135 billion, reflecting a surge in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise exports. The current account, also known as the country's balance of payments, shows how much foreign investment will be needed to finance <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trade deficit. Unless something is done to jump-start <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s stalled trade improvement, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, already the world's largest debtor country, will see that debt top $ 1 trillion by 1992, the report predicted. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> net debtor status means that American assets have been traded to foreigners to pay for imported items such as cars and television sets. Because of this, foreigners now own more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investments than Americans hold overseas. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cline </PERSON>, a senior fellow at the institute and the author of the report, blamed the worsening trade picture on continuing high domestic demand in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which attracts imports and deflects American production away from export markets. To correct the situation, <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> said it is essential that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration reach agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on a credible program to meet the targets in the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law. The law calls for the deficit to be cut by $ 40 billion annually until the budget is in balance by 1993. <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration also needs to abandon the exchange rate policy <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has been pursuing since February 1987, which has aimed at stabilizing the value of the dollar. Instead, he said, the new administration needs to convince its major trading partners, in particular <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, that further devaluation of the dollar is needed to boost <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s competitiveness by making <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports cheaper on overseas markets <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> said the dollar needs to drop by 25 percent in value against the Japanese yen and by 20 percent in value against the West German mark. Such actions would put the trade deficit back on a declining path, reducing it to an annual rate of around $ 50 billion by 1992. <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> said trying to eliminate the entire trade deficit is not really feasible. `` To go all the way to a zero trade deficit would meet very stiff resistance'' from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading partners, <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I think it will be a major challenge just to get it down from $ 150 billion to $ 50 billion annually.'' <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> warns, as have other economists, that higher and higher levels of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign debt will ultimately lower <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s living standard as more and more resources are transferred to foreigners to pay interest payments on the debt. Such high levels of foreign borrowing also leave the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy vulnerable to foreign investors, who could suddenly decide they no longer want to hold <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investments, the study said. The growing debt burdens run the risk of a `` collapse of confidence in the dollar, triggering a further surge of inflation and interest rates _ and possibly a recession,'' the report said. `` At a minimum, they would weaken <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future growth by requiring persistently high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates to attract the needed foreign funds.'' The Cline study was based on computer models which simulated global trade flows based on various economic scenarios. Among the report's conclusions: _ Every percentage point boost in growth in the economies of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s major trading partners will result in a decline of $ 9 billion to $ 13 billion in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current account deficit by 1992 _ Every percentage point drop in the dollar's exchange value against other currencies produces a trade improvement of between $ 8 billion and $ 10 billion by 1992 as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods are made more competitive on overseas markets _ Each percentage point drop in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economic growth rate produces $ 15 billion in improvements in the deficit by lowering the demand for imports <PERSON> Cline </PERSON>'s study argues that major reductions in the federal budget deficit would dampen the growth of domestic demand, thus cutting <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s appetite for foreign goods. The study said that if the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> act quickly to implement the budget cuts, it will allow the necessary shift from a consumption-driven economy to an export-driven economy without a recession. The institute is a non-profit research organization which analyzes international economic issues.
