<HEAD>Paraguan Opposition Party Picks Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's chief opposition leader was picked at a weekend convention to run for president in May 1 elections, but his party vowed to boycott a new government in the event of election fraud. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, accepted his party's nomination Sunday night and vowed in his speech to defend <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s peasants and adopt economic policies to meet their needs. `` We will work with the clean hands and moral strength of the people,'' said <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>, 53, an economist and former university professor. He was exiled for seven years by the recently deposed government of Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Laino </PERSON> was expelled by <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s government in 1981 after writing a book about the business activities of Nicaraguan dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. The Nicaraguan, a friend of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, was granted asylum in <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> after his ouster in 1979. He was assassinated a year later on an <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION> street. `` Who is to say that on May 1, there will not be a new government composed of the glorious <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>?'' said <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>. He was the only candidate proposed for the presidency at the convention. <PERSON> Laino </PERSON> was carried from the convention hall on the shoulders of supporters following his acceptance speech. Delegates also approved candidates for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The May 1 elections will pick a president to fill the four years remaining in the five-year term of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who was ousted Feb. 3 by Gen. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>. The coup leader, who had served as an aide to <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, declared himself provisional president, dissolved <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and called for new elections. The <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest and best-organized party, has governed since 1947. It is expected to ratify <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> as its presidential candidate at a convention set for April 1. `` We know that many sectors of the government harbor hidden intentions of legitimizing the current de facto government,'' said <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> from 1967 to 1977. In recent weeks, the party has repeatedly criticized what it views as irregularities in voter registration, and it has suggested the <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> government might be trying to steal the election. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who had led <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> since a 1954 coup, was elected to an eighth consecutive term in February 1988 elections widely regarded as fraudulent. A plan adopted by <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>'s party calls for rejecting any seats won in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> if it deems the May 1 balloting to be fraudulent. Even if the elections are viewed as fair, the party still would withdraw from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> if electoral law reforms and changes in voter registration lists are not made before municipal elections scheduled for October 1990. The party claims voter lists are inflated in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. It also conditioned its participation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on revocation of a law which allows a president to serve an unlimited number of terms. It also demands repeal of two laws frequently used under <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> to crack down on dissidents and a ban on soldiers belonging to political parties.
