<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-seas standoff between the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and 250 U.S.-bound Haitians packed aboard a rickety 50-foot sailboat ended peacefully after a 30-hour confrontation that included threats babies would be thrown overboard. The Haitians agreed Sunday to the leave the boat and be returned to their country. No injuries were reported. One refugee woman was rescued after leaping into the sea and others vowed to throw their infant children overboard unless they were allowed to continue toward the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Petty Officer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Starks </PERSON>. `` It was really an ordeal and there were some very tense moments,'' said <PERSON> Starks </PERSON>. `` There was no idea what would happen and none of the Haitians had life jackets. There was a potential for a significant loss of life.'' The sailboat was discovered about 9 a.m. EST Saturday by the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutter Escape, which was transporting nearly 100 Haitians intercepted the previous day back to the impoverished nation, officials said. A rope was used to immobilize the rudder of the refugee vessel and four other <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> cutters were sent to the scene before the Haitians surrendered about 120 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Starks </PERSON> said. The cutters Escape and Steadfast were traveling toward <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION> today, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said. <PERSON> Starks </PERSON> said none of the refugees had weapons and no one was injured, although three ill Haitians were transported to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> Mia