 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said today on the eve of nationwide village elections that pro-Communist candidates who are voted into office in the balloting can serve if they are freely and fairly chosen. The military claims the rebels will use the vote to expand their base. Also today, the rebels claimed they have recovered from setbacks suffered during Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s administration, and police said three men shot up the home of an anti-communist activist near <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION>, killing three people, including the man's wife. On Tuesday, voters in the country's 42,000 villages, or `` barangays,'' will select about 287,567 local council members. The military claims the rebels are backing pro-Marxist candidates in hopes of solidifying their control in thousands of rural villages. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> was asked if the government would prevent rebel supporters from claiming council seats. The Communist Party of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> is banned, but Tuesday's balloting is supposed to be non-partisan. `` Well, if they have been elected legitimately, there has been no force, they will hold office,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> told reporters. `` We have to abide by the law.'' Col. <PERSON> Gerardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, intelligence chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constabulary </ORGANIZATION>, said the rebels hope to capture 60 percent of the village council seats in areas under their control. The rebels claim to control about 8,500 villages nationwide. But the Commission on Election puts the figure at about 2,800. The difference is believed to be in definitions of `` control.'' `` In remote, inaccessible areas, there is hardly any government presence,'' said election commissioner <PERSON> Haydee </PERSON> <PERSON> Yorac </PERSON>. `` So the party members are the ones who exercise the most serious influence.'' <PERSON> Hilario </PERSON> <PERSON> Davide </PERSON>, chairman of the election commission, said troops would be deployed in about 3,500 districts considered `` hot spots.'' In a statement marking Wednesday's 20th anniversary of the communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, rebel Chief of Staff <PERSON> Romulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON> claimed a force of 30,000 fighters deployed in 65 of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' 73 provinces, 800 of 1,500 cities and 12,000 villages and neighborhoods. `` NPA units have largely recovered from setbacks in 1985 and 1986 and have reconstituted guerrilla formations which had been reduced for a time,'' <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON> said. Civilian and military authorities claim the rebels are losing strength because of more effective counterinsurgency operations and improvements in the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> economy. They also maintain that the rebels lost much of their appeal following the February 1986 ouster of President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' authoritarian administration and the rise of Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to power Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has vowed to crush the insurgents before her term expires in 1992. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> was founded on March 29, 1969 by leftist intellectuals and remnants of the pro-Soviet HUK guerrillas, who waged an unsuccessful insurgency in the 1950s and 1960s. <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON> was captured in March 1987 but escaped last year from the stockade at <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s Camp Crame after attending a birthday party for his former jailer. In <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION>, 350 miles south of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, police and witnesses said gunmen late Sunday sprayed semi-automatic rifle fire on the home of <PERSON> Rogelio </PERSON> <PERSON> Nara </PERSON>, 37, in the village of <LOCATION> Kan-Irag </LOCATION> in the mountains above the city. <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION>'s wife and two male relatives were killed and two others were wounded, including <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION>'s nine-year-old daughter, police said. <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reforms </ORGANIZATION>, one of hundreds of government-backed anti-communist vigilante groups operating nationwide. Police said the attackers could have been rebels or relatives of a man killed by <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION> several years ago.
