<HEAD>Sheriff's Department To Comply With Grand Jury Recommendations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sheriff's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to comply with grand jury recommendations for ending abuse of jail inmates by a so-called `` Rambo Squad'' that allegedly stripped, chained and beat inmates, a spokesman said. The grand jury investigated allegations by more than 100 people who said they had been abused or held naked in jail cells after being arrested for misdemeanor offenses which usually were alcohol-related. No indictments were issued, but the panel's report, released last week following a nine-month investigation, criticized <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> and his top assistants for failing to provide the leadership to stop a group of deputies at the <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cajon </ORGANIZATION> jail from preying on inmates. The grand jury found that the deputies found `` delight in cruelty to others.'' The panel also cited coverups and mismanagement by jail supervisors, and said many deputies looked the other way while inmates were being assaulted or harassed. Department spokesman Lt. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulmer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> has reviewed the 20-page report and `` there is absolutely nothing he disagrees with.'' `` He thinks all the recommendations are good, and he would like to implement them as soon as possible,'' <PERSON> Fulmer </PERSON> said. The panel's recommendations include the creation of an Inspections and Control Division; a strengthening of the department's Internal Affairs Division; required filing of detailed reports of physical confrontations between prisoners and deputies; and tougher standards for the selection and performance of jail training officers.
