<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and Christian army gunners hammered each other's positions in and around <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> today after random bombardment of the capital forced residents to spend the Easter holiday underground. Police said three civilians were killed and 13 wounded in the hostilities overnight and during the morning. The casualties raised the toll to 97 dead and 339 wounded since the latest round of fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war broke out March 8. The rocket and artillery barrages in the capital tapered off at daybreak. But heavy duels resounded in the mountains overlooking <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, police said. It was the fourth consecutive night that barrages on both Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> have confined civilians to basements and bomb shelters. The Syrians and their allies have also ordered a blockade of east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and nearby Christian communities, home of about 1 million people. Syrian forces and allied Druse gunners pounded east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> with rocket barrages of up to 60 rounds per minute during the night. The bombardment set fires at a fuel tank at the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port and the city's main power plant, police said. The Christian army units retaliated with barrages from 155mm howitzers. Until the damaged plant is repaired, authorities will be able to provide electricity for just four hours a day. The fighting pits army Commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> units against an alliance of Syrian troops and militiamen of Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> contends the Syrians, who intervened 13 years ago as peacekeepers, have turned into an occupation force by taking sides with Moslems and Druse. He heads a Christian military Cabinet in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s divided government. Syrians back the rival Moslem government. The Christian leader has declared a `` war of liberation'' to drive out the 40,000 Syrian troops. He has vowed to fight on even at the risk of destroying <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, today rejected <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s accusations. `` The Syrian army entered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1976 at the request of the then reigning Lebanese government. This request was later endorsed by the Arab League, of which <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is a founding member,'' <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> said. He said any demand for a Syrian pullout should be made by a united <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> government `` which is not present at the moment.'' The latest violence began after <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> imposed a blockade on milita-run ports. The militias skim taxes that would otherwise go to the government.
