<HEAD>Abortion Rallies Over, Operation Rescue Leader Jailed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 300 anti-abortion protesters remained in jail this morning, where their leader claimed police used excessive force in making arrests and accused the media of a `` pro-death'' bias. The Operation Rescue protesters spent Easter behind bars, sometimes singing hymns, refusing to take the legal steps that would have allowed them to leave jail because they wanted to dramatize their cause. The group's jailed leader, <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, spent part of the day calling journalists to complain that they failed to show pictures of aborted fetuses that might show the public what abortion really entails. He opened the New York-based group's Holy Week protests Thursday by appearing at a news conference with a small, white coffin that contained what he said was an aborted 19-week-old fetus. After opening the coffin lid he left, challenging the media to televise the remains. `` The media is the greatest perpetrator of this holocaust because they're hiding the truth from the public,'' <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> said Sunday. `` It's not a matter of taste. The majority of the media elite are pro-death and reduce this to a war of words, and it's a war of bodies, dead bodies.'' The protesters are the latest of more than 21,000 to be arrested nationally since 1987, mostly for blocking clinics where abortions are performed. As part of their effort to focus attention on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s reconsideration of its 1973 decision legalizing abortion, 252 men and at least 50 women stayed in jail Sunday by refusing to provide their names to police or to sign misdemeanor trespassing citations. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, a former car salesman, and three others could face more serious charges: They remained jailed today for investigation of felony conspiracy to encourage others to commit a crime. `` This felony charge is a joke,'' he said. `` How can you have a felony conspiracy to commit a misdemeanor trespass? That's ludicrous. He alleged <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> police used excessive force when they arrested 750 protesters during a six-hour standoff outside a clinic Saturday. More than 1,000 anti-abortion activists were arrested during three days of protests in Cypress, <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Officers' treatment of protesters, he charged, `` was completely uncalled for and unprofessional. You do n't twist people's arms to the point were they're screaming in pain and sticking two fingers up their nose.'' One demonstrator's arm and wrist were broken in a scuffle with police Saturday, Operation Rescue said. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> police Cmdr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> said Sunday that the group was exaggerating the incidents. Police Chief <PERSON> Daryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> said officers used a `` pain compliance hold'' in the arrests. And he said he would ask the city attorney to sue Operation Rescue for the $ 60,000 to $ 100,000 the demonstration cost the city.
