<FIRST>r a PM-Drugs-Surplus     03-27 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Surplus,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Bank Sees Surplus Due To Drug Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cash surplus at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> here has jumped from $ 165 million in 1985 to $ 3.8 billion in 1988, and authorities believe the 23-fold increase is largely because of laundered drug money moving through banks. `` It is a good indicator that we are awash with dope money being laundered through <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, not just from the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area but from elsewhere in the country,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> said. `` Staggering amounts of cash are being funneled into the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area for laundering here.'' Despite hefty fines levied against some of the state's largest financial institutions, drug officials say the illegal money is being funneled into the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> after being laundered through banks. Laundering is the process of passing money through enough transactions that it is hard to trace. It may arrive at a bank as a legitimate business deposit. The money may then be transferred to foreign bank accounts controlled by drug kingpins without traffickers having to smuggle cash out of the country. <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, which had a reputation of being the hub for drug laundering, saw its Federal Reserve surplus drop from a high of $ 6 billion in 1985 to $ 4.8 billion in 1988, still the largest surplus in the country. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lochridge </PERSON> said the trend `` validates <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> as the new money-laundering and drug financial center in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The Federal Reserve System is the nation's central bank, managing the money supply by controlling how much cash member banks must keep liquid instead of loaning out. About 40 percent of the nation's banks belong to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>. When deposits at a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> district branch exceed the branch's cash shipments back to its member banks, that district is said to have a cash surplus. Only 10 of the 35 branches of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reported cash surpluses last year. After <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, the others are <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, with a $ 1.9 billion surplus; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, $ 511 million; <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, $ 484 million; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, $ 399 million; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, $ 367 million; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, $ 118 million; <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, $ 45 million; and <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, $ 15 million.
