<HEAD>Premier's Party Suffers Big Defeat in Local Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> suffered a crushing defeat in nationwide local elections, winning only three mayoral races in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s 67 provincial capitals, unofficial returns showed today. The governing party finished third in the provincial assembly elections behind the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Populist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the chief opposition group, and the conservative <ORGANIZATION> True </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of former six-time Premier <PERSON> Suleyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Demirel </PERSON>, according to nearly complete tallies provided by state radio and the <ORGANIZATION> Anatolia </ORGANIZATION> news agency. Opposition parties described Sunday's elections as a referendum on <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>'s free-market economic policies. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> had said he would quit if opposition gains were large enough to make it difficult for him to govern. But today, <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> said he would stay on until the next elections scheduled for 1992. `` he nation gave us a mandate until 1992, we will be serving the nation until then,'' the 61-year-old premier told a news conference `` The people knew the party in power would not change as a result of these elections. They wanted to give us a message: to bring down inflation faster,'' <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> said. He said `` A little warning was intended by the voters but it went a bit too far.'' <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> promised changes in the Cabinet sometime this week. Voters elected more than 326,000 mayors, provincial assembly members, city council members, village leaders and neighborhood representatives. In the provincial assembly elections, the Social Democrats gained 28 percent of the nationwide vote, and the True Path had 25.5 percent, the returns showed. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>'s party was in third place with 22 percent. Among the smaller parties, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of former Premier <PERSON> Bulent </PERSON> <PERSON> Ecevit </PERSON> got 9 percent, the Moslem fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Prosperity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> 9.5 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> 4.5 percent, the rightist <ORGANIZATION> Reformist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> 1 percent, and the rest was scattered among independent candidates. <PERSON> Demirel </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> should quit because of the results. `` He said he would pack up and go, and if he is true to his word, he should do so,'' <PERSON> Demirel </PERSON> told reporters. `` I am sure he will not try to run the country on support based on 22 percent of the votes.'' <PERSON> Erdal </PERSON> <PERSON> Inonu </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Populist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, also claimed a win over the <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Inonu </PERSON>, a nuclear physics professor turned politician, declared, `` The people accomplished a real spring cleaning, making it clear who they wanted to see in power.'' Several Motherland members asked for early parliamentary elections. `` Not early but immediate elections should be held,'' said <PERSON> Fahrettin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON>, minister of energy. Five years ago in local assembly elections, <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> gained 41 percent of the vote, the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Populists </ORGANIZATION> won 22 percent, and the True Path won 13 percent. The rest of the votes were divided between three other parties. On Sunday, the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> won 30 mayorships out of 53 already decided; the <ORGANIZATION> True </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> won 15 and the Motherland party won three. In the last local elections, the <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> captured 54 mayorships in the 67 provincial capitals. Also on the ballots Sunday were mayor's races in 1,917 small towns. Social Democrat candidates ousted <LOCATION> Motherland </LOCATION> mayors in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s three largest cities: <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Izmir </LOCATION> Political analysts attributed <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>'s loss to inflation, which reached 75 percent last year, his family's high-spending lifestyle, charges of nepotism, and allegations of corruption in high places. Ballots are counted by hand. Complete unofficial results are not expected until Tuesday.
