<HEAD>Reports Say Iran's Navy Seized Yacht</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Media reports said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s navy seized a yacht with as many as five members of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s royal family and four Britons aboard, but officials in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> denied knowledge of the incident. Diplomatic sources in <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> said Iranians have told them the vessel was taken when it strayed into Iranian waters, but that `` the boat and its occupants have been released.'' Media reports said members of the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> royal family were aboard the boat, but one diplomatic source said he was told by an Iranian diplomat that no <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> royal family members were aboard. Diplomatic sources told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the boat had four British male crew and technicians and two prominent Arabs. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, would not elaborate on their identity. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> made no public comment on the reports, which surfaced Sunday in a report by the Kuwaiti newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Anbaa </ORGANIZATION>. The newspaper reported the yacht was seized by the Iranians in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> on Thursday while sailing from <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The Independent Television News of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> quoted diplomatic sources in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> as saying the royal family members were <PERSON> Kuwaitis </PERSON> and the four Britons were women. The British <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said: `` All our investigations and inquiries have drawn a complete blank.'' Asked whether that meant no yacht was seized, a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said: `` Not that we can tell.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity. Officials in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> also denied knowledge of the reported seizure. Shipping executives and fishermen in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> have referred to cases of `` piracy'' in which they say Iranians have captured at least two expensive boats in recent months. The boats' occupants reportedly were free unharmed.
