<HEAD>Court Will Decide Liquor-Labeling Issue in North Dakota Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether states may impose labelng and reporting requirements on liquor sold at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases within their borders. The court said it will review a ruling that such <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> regulation of liquor sold at two military bases in that state violates federal policy. A <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> law requires all liquor sold in the state to be distributed through a state-controlled system. State officials sought to require out-of-state liquor distributors to put a label on each bottle sold at the Grand Forks and <ORGANIZATION> Minot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Bases. The labels were to say the liquor is for consumption only at the military installations. The state also wanted suppliers to report monthly on how much liquor they shipped into the state. The rules were designed to prevent liquor intended for the two military enclaves from being sold elsewhere in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. The federal government challenged the regulations, arguing they violated a federal policy aimed at assuring liquor sold at clubs and stores on military bases would be purchased by the government for the lowest possible price. Profits from the military base sales are used to pay for recreational activities. Federal officials said it could cost the government $ 200,000 to $ 250,000 more each year if the labeling and reporting regulations were enforced in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. They said the rules would force them to purchase more liquor from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> distributors at higher prices. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last September that the state regulations must give way to the federal policy. The appeals court rejected the state's argument that it was empowered to impose the regulations by the 21st Amendment to the Constitution, which repealed Prohibition and gave states sweeping control over liquor distribution. `` We conclude that the 21st Amendment provides no basis for regulating the means by which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has sought to order military liquor procurement and to provide for the welfare and morale activities of military personnel,'' the appeals court said. The National Beer Wholesalers' Association supported <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s appeal. The association said there is `` uncontradicted evidence ... that <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> was seriously concerned about the problem of diversion of liquor from military reservations.'' The case is <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-926.
