<HEAD>China's Foreign Minister Defends Human Rights Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign minister said today some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were ill-informed about human rights questions in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and threatened progress toward close bilateral relations. On Sino-Soviet relations, meanwhile, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON> told reporters that even after Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> visits <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in May, there will be some way to go before differences between the two countries are resolved. Since diplomatic ties were formed a decade ago, relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` enjoy vast potential and the prospects are very good,'' <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said. But he warned against interference in Chinese internal matters that he said `` was not in the interest of friendly relations.'' <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> called for a `` new pattern'' of relations based on mutual trust, and had sharp words for members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who have criticized <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s lack of democratic reform and its human rights record in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. `` A small number of people in the American <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are actually very ill-informed about the situation in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. They have very strong prejudice.'' The Chinese government last week criticized both the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for statements over the declaration of martial law in the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> following pro-independence riots there this month. Human rights, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said, are a matter of basic questions such as providing adequate food and education and `` are inseparable with the actual condition of the country involved.'' He also said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressional criticisms of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s family planning policies that try to keep couples from having more than one child were `` fairly absurd.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in recent years has withheld funds for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> family planning programs on the grounds that money going to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> backs up strict birth control policies that have led to forced abortions. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which supports the anti-Vietnamese resistance in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, backs the dispatch of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force after <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> ends its 10-year occupation. But, he said, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is not preparing to send peace troops to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The question of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> will be high on the agenda when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> meets Chinese leaders in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said. The summit, the first between the two countries in 30 years, will normalize long-strained relations, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said, but does n't mean that all major obstacles to better relations will be removed. Soviet support for <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s invasion of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> is regarded by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as the most serious obstacle to better ties between <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.
