<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Gebbie,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Let Stand Damage Award to Former Oregon Medical Examiner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a $ 300,000 award won by <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s former chief medical examiner from the woman who fired him following news reports that he had sold body parts to finance parties in the morgue. The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by <PERSON> Kristine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON>, administrator of the State Health Division, aimed at overturning the award won by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. A federal jury ruled that <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> deprived <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> of his constitutionally protected liberty interests without due process of law when she fired him in 1985. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> had maintained a bank account, in his name but with the knowledge of everyone in his office, for money paid for pituitary glands and other body parts removed during autopsies in the state coroner's office. The money was used for various amenities in the medical examiner's office. When <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> announced <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s firing on Oct. 3, 1985, she issued a press release in which she said <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> had `` knowingly violated public trust and confidence'' through his `` systematic 16-year diversion of public funds.'' In upholding the jury verdict last Oct. 31, the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> presented undisputed evidence that <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> charged him with: _ Violating the public trust _ Diverting state funds for his own use _ Establishing a `` slush fund. _ Causing the state to be billed for toxicological reports made in connection with private autopsies he performed The appeals court added, `` There was sufficient evidence presented from which a jury could reasonably infer that the charges were both contested and false.'' In the appeal acted on today, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> Solicitor General <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Linder </PERSON> argued for <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> that the appeals court ruling places government employers in an `` untenable position.'' The appeal said the 9th Circuit court's ruling gives no clear guidelines for `` government's responsiveness to the performance of its high-level officials and its ability to speak to the public it serves.'' The appeal also contended that <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> was entitled to qualified immunity from <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s lawsuit because `` she acted in unquestioned good faith and the law concerning liberty interests and name-clearing hearings is far from settled.'' The case is <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, 88-1299.
