<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Larsen     03-27 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Larsen,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact Dismissal of Suit Against Pennsylvania Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to review a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> judge's lawsuit against two newspapers that reported on what was to have been a confidential state investigation of him. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s suit against The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> and The <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Gazette </ORGANIZATION>. As a result of various articles appearing in both newspapers about <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>, the state's <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquiry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> began an investigation in mid-1982. In his suit, <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> said the articles portrayed him as being involved in `` political activity, racism, favoritism and influence-peddling.'' Completed in May 1983, the state board's investigation exonerated <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> of any wrongdoing. During the investigation, both newspapers published reports about the board's supposedly secret proceedings. Some articles even contained excerpts of hearing transcripts. Those reports were the basis of <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s suit, in which he charged the newspapers with obtaining the transcripts illegally and publishing only selected excerpts that placed him in a false light. The suit, which sought monetary damages, also claimed that the articles invaded <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s privacy and violated the confidentiality provisions of state law. A state trial judge dismissed most of the lawsuit's counts, and that dismissal was upheld by a state appeals court. The appeals court relied heavily on a 1978 ruling by the nation's highest court in a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> case. In that decision, the justices said the free-press protections in the Constitution's First Amendment mean newspapers can not be criminally punished for publishing truthful information about secret governmental proceedings. The decision struck down a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law that made it a crime to report about a state judicial commission's confidential investigations into judges' fitness to hold office. The <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> appeals court ruled that allowing <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s civil suit would, like <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s criminal law, violate free-press rights `` The imposition of monetary damages -LRB- civil sanctions -RRB- can be just as inimical to and an encroachment of one's First Amendment guarantees as criminal sanctions,'' the state court said. The <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to hear <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s ensuing appeal last Oct. 31. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> argued that the state courts wrongly concluded that the newspapers' free-press rights would be harmed if <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> were allowed to sue over violations of state confidentiality provisions. Lawyers for the newspapers urged the justices to reject the appeal. They noted, among other things, that the state court rulings left <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> free to amend his complaint to explain his assertion that confidential information was obtained `` illegally.'' The case is <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1274.
