<HEAD>Warmer Than Normal For Early Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The central part of the nation is basking in temperatures more like early summer than early spring as a pair of weather systems pull air up from the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Temperatures in the 70s and 80s, as much as 30 degrees warmer than normal, were predicted today over the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the central half of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the central Plains. On Sunday, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, tied its record of 75 degrees and <LOCATION> Ottumwa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, tied its record of 78. <LOCATION> Dodge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, hit a non-record 85 degrees and <LOCATION> Moline </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, hit a non-record 80. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, it was 76, one degree shy of the record. But the warmth will gradually diminish and move eastward over the next couple of days, with the central states cooling by 10 to 20 degrees and the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> warming, said <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s public service unit in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. `` The eastern seaboard should be expecting temperatures around 70 through Friday, especially around the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area,'' he said today. The warm air is being pumped northward by the clockwise flow around a high pressure area off the central <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and the counterclockwise flow around a low over <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, he said.
