<HEAD>Yeltsin Elected To Moscow Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout to recast, update to conform to developments,
provide results from election commission. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Maverick populist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> savored his political comeback today as election officials announced he had trounced a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> loyalist for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s sole at-large seat in the new national legislature. `` It's hard to say what my spirit is more full of, joy or concern about what I realistically can do to help Muscovites,'' the 58-year-old <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told several hundred applauding workers at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, where he is first deputy chairman. <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Orlov </PERSON>, chairman of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s election commission, said <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> won 89.4 percent of the vote Sunday. His opponent, <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>, received 6.9 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, who was ousted as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Communist Party boss in 1987, has accused the party's elite of trying to discredit him and had said he feared votes might be tampered with to cheat him out of victory. The former protege of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> campaigned against the privileges afforded high-ranking Soviet officials and called for faster reforms to improve living standards for everyone. His opponent, <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>, the 51-year-old director of the ZIL limousine plant, has carefully followed the party line in most matters. The cars made at his factory are a prized perquisite of high-ranking officials. <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON> had said his top priority is to end food shortages by providing more machinery to farmers and improving storage and processing facilities. Large pro-Yeltsin rallies were held in the capital in the closing days of the campaign and the former <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party leader became something of a symbol for people expressing a desire for truly representative government. ocal <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> election officials spent all night counting votes after Sunday's election for the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies _ the country's first contested elections in more than 70 years. `` We have been sitting and waiting since last evening for the final votes; we are unshaven and have had no sleep,'' <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubivsky </PERSON>, a member of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Volgograd </LOCATION> district, said by telephone. <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudyakov </PERSON>, a city council member, said the votes, initially counted at local election districts, were being recounted at the city election headquarters and the information was fed into computers for final tabulation. He said representatives of <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON> were at the council building to oversee the recount. Of more than 2,000 Soviets interviewed by Western correspondents at polling places after the voting, 1,734 were for <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> and 162 for <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>. Others either refused to disclose how they voted or expressed opposition to either candidate. After casting his ballot, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> claimed many Soviets were worried about voting fraud, and he complained that the elections were not completely democratic. `` People are worried about the election results, worried that there will be deviations at election stations during vote counting,'' he told reporters. `` Everything is troubling them.'' He said the campaign was `` not fully democratic'' but was a `` big step forward'' from previous one-candidate balloting. He said the real test of democracy will be whether the vote count is fair. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who brought <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> into <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership in 1985 and two years later oversaw his ouster on charges of making political mistakes and displaying personal ambition, said criticism of party officials is normal during campaigns.
