<HEAD>Government Releases Report On Gandhi Killing, Aide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today released a report that accused an aide to Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of links to the assassination of his mother. Officials said investigators later found the aide was not involved. The findings of a special commission report on Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s 1984 slaying were withheld for three years, but a newspaper account of the report prompted opposition legislators to demand its release. When <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> initially refused, opposition legislators walked out of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and some were suspended for a week for misbehavior. The commission report, released to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, accused <PERSON> Rajendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s personal secretary, of facilitating the assassination. But it added: `` The possiblity of someone else being involved along with Mr. <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> can not be excluded.'' A government memorandum also released today said investigators had checked the accusations and found <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> `` had no hand in the conspiracy for the assassination of Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and that there was nothing to indicate that Mr. <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> was in any way involved in the crime or conspiracy.'' <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON>, 52, left his post shortly after Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s death but returned to government last month as a key adviser to <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. He was not immediately available for comment. Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was shot in the garden of her <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> residence by two Sikh bodyguards as she walked to a television interview. One of the Sikhs, <PERSON> Beant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, was shot and killed by other bodyguards minutes after the assassination, and the other, <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, was convicted of murder and hanged on Jan. 6. A third Sikh, <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, was convicted of conspiracy and also hanged. In releasing the report to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, Home Minister <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said another special investigating team also had `` unraveled a conspiracy.'' He said additional charges would be filed, but did not say when or against whom. According to the report, the commission did not rule out involvement of an unspecified foreign agency that might have used the assassins `` as unwitting instruments.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has long accused neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of training and arming Sikh militants. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has denied the charge. <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> passed a resolution in 1986 allowing the government to withhold the report in the interest of national security. But on March 14, the <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> newspaper published parts of the report that alleged <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> lied during questioning and gave unconvincing explanations about entries in his diary, including the name of one of Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s assassins. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> released the report only after members of his <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> threatened to do so. The government says Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was killed in revenge for an army raid she ordered on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, the holiest Sikh shrine. At least 1,200 people, many of them Sikhs, were killed in the June 1984 raid, which was aimed at ousting Sikh extremists who had turned the shrine into an armed fortress. Sikh militants began fighting in 1982 for an independent homeland. Sikhs, who comprise 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people, claim discrimination by the Hindus, who make up 80 percent of the population.
