<HEAD>Rajavi's Sister Reportedly Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s main rebel opposition group said today that the sister of its leader, <PERSON> Massoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajavi </PERSON>, has been executed after being tortured in an Iranian prison. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> had no immediate comment on the allegation. In a statement sent to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>, or the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warriors </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Monireh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajavi </PERSON> was arrested with her husband, <PERSON> Asghar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazemi </PERSON>, in 1982. The statement said the couple's only offense was that the woman was the sister of Rajavi, who in addition to being the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahadeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>'s leader, also is commander of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of Iranian dissident factions based in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. It said <PERSON> Nazemi </PERSON> was executed in 1985 and his wife was tortured for several years before being executed. She was 38 years old, the statement said. The rebels did not identify the prison where she was held or give the date and method of the alleged execution. Iranians usually execute women by firing squads. Men are usually hanged. The <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION> statement said the couple has two daughters but it did not say where they live or how old they are. The London-based human rights group, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, as well as other human rights organizations and some governments have condemned <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for executing thousands of political prisoners since August. In that month authorities began a crackdown against dissidents after a cease-fire halted eight years of war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> government has said most people executed recently were drug traffickers.
