<HEAD>Court Will Restudy Death Penalty Issue in Pennsylvania Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said today it will restudy how far states may go in limiting a jury's discretion to choose life or death for convicted murderers. The court agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s death penalty law violates the Constitution by improperly limiting jury discretion. It will hear an appeal by <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON>, sentenced to die for a Sept. 9, 1983, murder committed during a robbery. <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> and three others picked up hitchhiker <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Smithburger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Fayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The jury found that <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> robbed the man of $ 13 and then fatally shot him in the back of the head. The same jury sentencted <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> to death. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s death penalty statute says, `` The verdict must be a sentence of death if the jury unanimously finds at least one aggravating circumstance ... and no mitigating circumstance.'' The only aggravating factor the jury found was that <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> killed <PERSON> Smithburger </PERSON> during a felony _ namely robbery. <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> did not submit any mitigating factors during the sentencing phase of the case. The <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last October that the state law does not violate the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s prohibition against the mandatory death penalty. The state court said under the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law `` an individual may thwart the imposition of the death penalty by offering evidence of mitigating circumstances concerning his character, record and the circumstances of the offense. Since -LRB- <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> -RRB- refused to present any evidence of mitigation, there was nothing to block'' imposition of the death penalty. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 said juries may not be precluded from considering mitigating evidence. Lawyers for <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law works like a mandatory capital punishment act because the jury is misled into believing it has a moral duty to impose the death penalty in such cases. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law enforcement officials argued that the state death penalty statute is constitutional because, despite its mandatory language, nothing prevents the defendant from presenting mitigating evidence to offset the presentation of aggravating circumstances. The case is <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, 88-6222.
