<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Iowa Ruling on Hospital Chaplain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 15-24, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that a public hospital does not violate the constitutionally required separation of church and state by having a chaplain on its payroll. The court, without comment, refused to hear an appeal by three <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> atheists who said taxpayers should not be forced to fund a chaplain's salary at a county-run hospital. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last September upheld the employment of a chaplain at <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Broadlawns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>. Three avowed atheists _ <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, his daughter, <PERSON> Courtney </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON> _ said their rights were violated because the government was sponsoring religious activity. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1983 that paying chaplains to lead daily prayers in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and state legislatures does not violate the Constitution. The court cited a long tradition, 200 years old in the case of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, to support its ruling. The <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> atheists noted that the chaplain at <LOCATION> Broadlawns </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Alzeno </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, was hired in 1985 and her duties are more than ceremonial. A deacon of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> counsels patients, their families and hospital workers and conducts religious services and Bible study classes at the hospital. She is paid $ 23,000 a year. The 8th Circuit court said her duties serve a secular purpose, enhancing the hospital's `` wholistic treatment approach.'' `` The purpose of the chaplaincy was the same as that of the hospital generally, to help patients get well or at least to provide the best care possible for those who would not get well,'' the appeals court said. It added that there was evidence Ms. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' presence did not advance religion unconstitutionally because she refrained from proselytizing _ seeking religious converts. The appeals court also said Ms. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> may have reduced entanglement between the church and state at the hospital because there is less need for hospital officials to supervise volunteer chaplains who worked at <LOCATION> Broadlawns </LOCATION> before she was hired. It is part of Ms. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' job to make sure that the volunteer chaplains are not proselytizing, the appeals court said. It also noted that many patients at the hospital are committed involuntarily or are prisoners treated there. Comparing Ms. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> to a military chaplain, the appeals court said many patients would have no alternative religious counseling if she were not available. The appeals court said, however, that Ms. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> should be permitted to give only secular counseling to hospital employees. In other action, the court: _ Said it will restudy how far states may go in limiting a jury's discretion to choose life or death for convicted murderers. The court agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s death penalty law violates the Constitution by improperly limiting jury discretion. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s death penalty statute says: `` The verdict must be a sentence of death if the jury unanimously finds at least one aggravating circumstance ... and no mitigating circumstance.'' _ Refused to review a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> judge's lawsuit against two newspapers that reported on what was to have been a confidential state investigation of him. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s suit against The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> and The <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Gazette </ORGANIZATION>. _ Agreed to decide whether states may impose labeling and reporting requirements on liquor sold at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases within their borders. The court said it will review a ruling that such <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> regulations of liquor sold at two military bases in that state violates federal policy. _ Let stand a $ 300,000 award won by <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s former chief medical examiner from the woman who fired him following news reports that he had sold body parts to finance parties in the morgue. The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by <PERSON> Kristine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON>, administrator of the State Health Division, aimed at overturning the award won by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. A federal jury ruled that <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> deprived <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> of his constitutionally protected liberty interests without due process of law when she fired him in 1985. The chaplain case is <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Broadlawns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1286.
