<HEAD>Rebels Say 53 Soldiers Killed, Five Aircraft Shot Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas killed 53 Afghan army troops and shot down five aircraft in fighting around <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s strategic eastern city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, the insurgents claimed today. However, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON>, an Afghan government spokesman in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, said 190 insurgents died in the fighting around <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> and that two government soldiers and three civilians were killed. The contradicting claims could not be independently reconciled. The guerrilla-run <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said 53 communist troops died, 98 were wounded and five deserted in heavy fighting since Saturday. Insurgents shot down four helicopters and one airplane and captured several posts north of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, the agency claimed. It gave no estimate of guerrilla casualties. The guerrillas said heavy fighting continued around the city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, the airport to the southeast and in suburbs to the north. It said the Afghan air force has retaliated with heavy bombing, causing many high civilian casualties. <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> is the target of the guerrillas' first major offensive since Feb. 15, the date Soviet troops ended nine years of involvement in the Afghan war. Afghan government forces hold the country's key cities but guerrillas reportedly control about 90 percent of the countryside. The guerrillas are fighting to oust the communist government and establish an Islamic republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Afghan officials claim that Pakistani troops, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> military advisers, are fighting with the Pakistan-based guerrillas. All three countries supply the guerrillas but have denied that their military personnel are