<HEAD>Pathologists Checking Skeleton Found Near Place Lord Lucan Last Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEACHY HEAD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pathologists today examined a human skeleton found near the place Lord <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> last was seen alive following the murder of his children's nanny more than 14 years ago. But <LOCATION> Sussex </LOCATION> police said they thought it unlikely the remains were those of the missing earl. `` I would treat that with a great deal of skepticism,'' a police officer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. Police said until tests are completed on the skeleton, they will not know the age and sex of the person, the cause of death or how long ago it occurred. The skeleton was discovered Saturday in thick undergrowth on the Beachy Head coastal promontory. <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> was last seen alive at <LOCATION> Uckfield </LOCATION>, on <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s south coast, Nov. 7, 1974, the day <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivett </PERSON> was battered to death and <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> was attacked at the <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> family's <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> home. A car he borrowed was found abandoned at <LOCATION> Newhaven </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Beachy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Head </LOCATION>, 18 miles south of <LOCATION> Uckfield </LOCATION>. The police believe <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> killed the nanny in a dark basement, mistaking her for his estranged wife. They believe he then attacked <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> when he discovered his error. Five days later, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard issued a murder warrant for <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON>'s arrest, the first ever for a British peer. At an inquest, <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> accused her husband of being the man who attacked her, and a jury found him guilty of murder. <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> has been reported alive in various parts of the world, but police have not located him. Many believe <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> killed himself.
