<HEAD>Recipent of First Heart-Pancreas Transplant Recuperating</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 13th graf, ``The pancreas,'' with 2 grafs to elaborate
on diabetes-heart disease connection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A longtime diabetic whose pancreas had virtually destroyed his heart has been given another chance to live after doctors transplanted both organs in what is believed to be the first such operation ever. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, 45, was listed in serious condition today at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, and a spokeswoman said he was given an 80 percent chance of surviving a year. But before the surgery Saturday, the Silver Spring, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, physicist's chances of living even a week were slim. `` He was slipping away,'' his wife <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. `` When you see a loved on slipping away, you grab at anything that can help him ... I knew this was it. This was his last chance.'' <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>'s body has shown no signs of rejecting the organs, doctors said. And if all continues to go well, he could leave the hospital within weeks and eventually return to work as a senior scientist for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s Strategic Defense Initiative program, they said. <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> had undergone heart bypass surgery seven years ago, but the organ had begun deteriorating again over the past several months. He was hospitalized a week before a local donor was found. `` This is very fast,'' said <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brigham </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consortium </ORGANIZATION>. `` He was very, very fortunate in terms of timing.'' Doctors refused to identify the donor. <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>'s doctors decided to transplant his pancreas as well as his heart because they believed his severe diabetes would make management of a new heart difficult or impossible. Although the hospital does not have permission from the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to transplant the pancreas, surgeons went ahead with the double transplant anyway, fearing <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> would die if they waited. `` To our knowledge it's the first -LRB- heart-pancreas transplant -RRB- ever done,'' said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sollinger </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> surgeon considered one of the leading experts in pancreas transplants, was flown in by private jet Saturday morning. The procedure, which was divided into separate operations for each transplant, lasted the entire day. `` Everything proceeded wonderfully,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. Light, a member of the surgical team. `` The pancreas is working, and we think his diabetes is cured.'' The pancreas is supposed to produce insulin, the hormone that regulates the body's metabolism of sugar. When the organ does n't function properly, patients develop diabetes, and often have to rely on insulin injections and constant monitering to survive `` Diabetes can destroy the vascular system,'' said Ms. Dodge. `` Severe heart disease is a complication of diabetes.'' The one-year survival rate for patients receiving a new pancreas has been about 50 percent, compared with 85 percent for other organs, Light said. But improvements in management of anti-rejection drugs for the pancreas should improve <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>'s outlook, making his chances of surviving one year about 80 percent, doctors said.
