<SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,380</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. HOSPITAL CHAPLAIN The court let stand a ruling that a public hospital does not violate the constitutionally required separation of church and state by having a chaplain on its payroll. The court, without comment, refused to hear an appeal by three <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> atheists who said taxpayers should not be forced to fund a chaplain's salary at a county-run hospital. The case is <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Broadlawns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, 88-128 DEATH PENALTY The court said it will restudy how far states may go in limiting a jury's discretion to choose life or death for convicted murderers. The court agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s death penalty law violates the Constitution by improperly limiting jury discretion. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s death penalty statute says: `` The verdict must be a sentence of death if the jury unanimously finds at least one aggravating circumstance ... and no mitigating circumstance.'' The case is <PERSON> Blystone </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, 88-6222. JUDGE ` S LAWSUIT The court refused to review a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> judge's lawsuit against two newspapers that reported on what was to have been a confidential state investigation of him. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON>'s suit against The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> and The <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Gazette </ORGANIZATION>. The case is <PERSON> Larsen </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1274. LIQUOR The court agreed to decide whether states may impose labeling and reporting requirements on liquor sold at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases within their borders. The court said it will review a ruling that such <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> regulations of liquor sold at two military bases in that state violates federal policy. The case is <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-926. MEDICAL EXAMINER The court let stand a $ 300,000 award won by <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s former chief medical examiner from the woman who fired him following news reports that he had sold body parts to finance parties in the morgue. The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by <PERSON> Kristine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON>, administrator of the State Health Division, aimed at overturning the award won by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. A federal jury ruled that <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> deprived <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> of his constitutionally protected liberty interests without due process of law when she fired him in 1985. The case is <PERSON> Gebbie </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, 88-1299.
