tment fund losses and for conspiring to cover them up. The two articles added today accuse him of putting an unqualified person in control of the state's investment portfolio after two previous treasury employees left and having the treasurer's office charge a service fee for handling investments in the fund. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON>, Gainer, and former Gov. <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> made up the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> when the losses occurred in the consolidated investment fund. The board had general supervisory control over the fund. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON>'s office had direct investment powers. Committee members were angered by statements <PERSON> Gainer </PERSON> made to them during 10 days of testimony on the impeachment issue. They believed he should have been more active in the fund's supervision. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> left office in January after being unseated by <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> in last year's general election.
