<FIRST>u a AM-TrailofTears Bjt   03-27 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trail of Tears, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cherokees Observe 150th Anniversary of End of Tragic Removal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAHLEQUAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is no celebration the <LOCATION> Cherokees </LOCATION> plan this week, although spring brings a special joy in the adopted homeland where the tribe ended its greatest tragedy 150 years ago. In the winter of 1838-39, thousands of Cherokees died on a forced march from their homes in the southeastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to what is now northeastern <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. The path is known as the Trail of Tears. On Friday and Saturday, the tribe observes the sesquicentennial of that time. The last of 14 groups of Cherokees escorted by federal troops arrived in late March 1839. <PERSON> Wilma </PERSON> <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON>, chief of the nation's second-largest <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> tribe, said <PERSON> Cherokees </PERSON> decided to mark the sesquicentennial after some hesitation because of the sensitivity that lingers over those days. The tribe settled on a commemoration only after wagon hobbyists not affiliated with the tribe re-traced the Trail of Tears last fall. Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> noted most Cherokees made the trek by foot, some in shackles. `` It was n't a friendly removal,'' she said. `` I think there are a number of people who have concerns,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON>, chief since 1985. `` I think it's healthy for us to look back -LRB- and show -RRB- respect for our ancestors. `` It helps to place our present problems in a historical context. But I certainly understand the concerns of people about looking at this issue. `` I think for us it's a very solemn, very emotional time. We look at it as something that happened to our family.'' Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> said the observance provides `` a chance to do some public education about our history.'' `` There's so little accurate information about what modern American Indians are like. There's a vacuum,'' she said. Most Americans know only the Indians they see depicted in <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> movies, Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> said. In the tribe's capital of <LOCATION> Tahlequah </LOCATION>, a university city of 10,000, there will be speeches, story-telling and flute playing. A tree will be planted in honor of the estimated 4,000 Cherokees who died along the trail. Donated hogs will be cooked in huge black kettles on the grounds of a historic home. There will be free corn bread and beans, eggs and wild onions. `` This is what the Indians of the hills eat ... whatever food they could find and forage,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ketcher </PERSON>, deputy chief of the tribe, who remembers when his own relatives would not discuss the tragedy. Those forced westward included Cherokees who owned plantations and had assimilated into the dominant white culture. But the tribe had its own government and its own written language when President <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> ordered the Cherokees removed from land sought by white settlers. <PERSON> Ketcher </PERSON>'s great-grandparents were on the trail, uprooted from northern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. `` I never did hear about the trail when I was growing up _ nothing, not anything,'' <PERSON> Ketcher </PERSON> said. `` Was it just an attempt to shut it out _ like it never happened? `` Many of them would just prefer to forget the whole thing, because it was such a tragic event in the lives of our people.'' Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON>, who keeps busy with speaking engagements nationwide, said the sesquicentennial should remind tribal members of their resiliency. `` It is intended to be sort of a solemn occasion ... But also at the same time look back about what happened after the Trail of Tears. We were able to bounce back in the 1800s,'' she said. A commemorative plaque depicts a legendary <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> bird arising from ashes to assume the form of a Cherokee warrior. The tribe arrived in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> politically divided over removal. But the tribe rebounded to re-form a government, enforce tribal laws and erect government buildings that still stand. It established some of the first schools west of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, including a school for women. `` Lots of people in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> believe that <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> history began with the Land Run -LRB- of 1889 -RRB-. We had been here for a couple of generations. We had made this area hospitable. We had settled it,'' she said. Today the Cherokee Nation's concerns focus on education, health care and employment, Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Cherokee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> has a booming greenhouse operation in <LOCATION> Tahlequah </LOCATION>, a defense contracting plant in <LOCATION> Stilwell </LOCATION> and industrial tracts, but economic development in the rural areas remains a major concern. `` I share that frustration, I think, with every other small town in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
