<FIRST>r i AM-Election-Monitor     03-27 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Election-Monitor,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Group Says System Appears Efficient, but Abuses Possible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> human rights group that monitored the Soviet parliamentary elections said Monday the system appeared to be efficient but there were flaws that could have led to rigging the results. Soviet newspapers reported some voters were disenfranchised because of election difficulties. <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Orlov </PERSON>, the chairman of the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> election commission, acknowledged some snags developed in Sunday's voting, the first multicandidate elections in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 70 years. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carliner </PERSON>, an attorney with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference that six delegates visited 17 polling stations in eight election districts. `` The process appeared efficient and officials took their duty quite seriously,'' he said. `` It was clear that they did not try in any way to influence the voters.'' Voters interviewed by the delegation `` were satisfied that their ballots were secret and sacred and would be counted,'' <PERSON> Carliner </PERSON> said. There were possibilities to commit election fraud, however, mainly because there were n't enough Soviet observers to monitor all polling stations, he said. At several polling stations, there were no observers or officials present by late afternoon. `` The lack of observers left open a chance to cheat,'' <PERSON> Carliner </PERSON> said. `` Anyone could have walked in, marked up a bunch of ballots and stuffed them into the box.'' In addition, special voting passes had been given to many people such as businessmen and tourists, allowing them to vote away from their residences, he said. That left the system open to abuse, he said. `` We ran up against masses of absolutely new moments, currents and problems,'' <PERSON> Orlov </PERSON> said from the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> City Council headquarters. `` Some things we did satisfactorily, some things did not get done until the end.'' Soviet newspapers carried complaints of people who said they were denied a chance to vote. `` In some election districts, a few disabled people were denied the voting right because of the inefficiency of voting commissions,'' <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said. In past elections, the disabled could request a ballot box be brought to their residences. If a person could not get to a polling station, a relative could take the person's internal passport and cast the vote by proxy. The newspaper said the election commission of the <LOCATION> Cheremushkinsky </LOCATION> district responded to the complaint by saying, `` They only had two portable ballot boxes and they were short of time.'' In other districts, residents did not receive the special mailed invitation cards needed to cast a ballot, it said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> group has monitored elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
