<HEAD>White House Says Gray Has Withdrawn Complaint About Aid Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New material, editing throughout with White House brushing
aside Gray complaint and rebuking him. ^By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House, trying to put an end to an embarrassing episode, today brushed aside a complaint from President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s legal counsel about the new Contra aid agreement and issued what amounted to a public rebuke of the official. In a highly unusual move, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> was quoted Sunday as saying the agreement encroached on the president's power to conduct foreign policy Privately, White House officials were perplexed that <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> would go public with a challenge to a policy <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had embraced. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sidestepped a question about whether he was angry at Gray. Mingling with thousands of children on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawn </LOCATION> during the annual Easter egg roll, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` On a day like this, I'm not angry at anybody.'' White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> met with chief of staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> today. `` They had a polite discussion about how things work in the White House,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. Asked why <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> would have felt that the agreement had not received proper legal review, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> replied, `` I just ca n't tell you what was in <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s mind That's more than I can handle.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>'s comments amounted to a rare public rebuke of another senior White House official. The press secretary was asked whether <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> had been told that he should work through proper channels instead of taking his complaints to the press. `` I do n't know that they did tell him that,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` I think that's a good idea. I'd tell him that.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> added, `` All the appropriate discussions have been commenced and completed with Mr. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> and he fully understands our position.'' The spokesman said, `` <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> simply explained his concerns and they were met and that's pretty much the end of it.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> played down the dispute and insisted that the accord does not surrender presidential power to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is a voluntary agreement,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said Sunday. `` ` You do not have the question arise here with respect to constitutional powers and prerogatives because the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is not imposing its will, in effect, through legislation.'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> himself tried to play down the dispute today during the daily meeting of senior White House officials. He told his colleagues that reports of his concerns were overstated and that he did n't think there were any problems with the agreement, according to an official who declined to be identified. `` He basically backed off,'' the official said. `` There's a lot of discussion of this and a feeling that it was really a somewhat bizarre occurrence and should n't have happened.'' The episode marked <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s second run-in with <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, one of the most powerful figures in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. Earlier, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> had raised questions about the propriety of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s financial holdings, and the secretary later disposed of the assets. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> did not return telephone calls seeking comment. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> had expressed concern in a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> interview about a provision giving any of four congressional committees the power to cut off aid to the Nicaraguan rebels after November if lawmakers conclude that the Contras'