<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> made her debut as chief <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman Monday, cautioning reporters that she was not knowledgeable about foreign policy and asking their `` patience and understanding.'' `` As you all know, I am not, and do not claim to be, an expert in foreign policy,'' <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said, reading a statement at the start of the daily <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> briefing. `` But I do claim to have a fair amount of experience in working with the press, and I do know this president and this secretary of state very well,'' she added. Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, 38, served as Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s spokeswoman when he was treasury secretary in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and worked for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> when he made his unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential nomination in 1980 Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, who is considered one of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s closest advisers, was confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> earlier this month. She has a tough act to follow in her job as assistant secretary of state for public affairs. Her predecessor, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, is a career foreign service officer with experience in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic posts overseas. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, who has been nominated ambassador to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, enjoyed close ties with former Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and was adept at handling the department's press corps. `` I have no intention of ever standing up here and winging it, or guessing, or misleading,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. `` When I do n't know something, I'll