<FIRST>r w AM-Poultry-Salmonella     03-27 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poultry-Salmonella,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says Sugar Can Cut Amount of Food Poisoning Bacteria in Chickens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that either ordinary lactose _ milk sugar _ or another sugar from a <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> plant can sharply reduce the amount of common food poisoning bacteria in the intestines of chickens destined for the consumer market. Preliminary tests showed that the number of salmonella bacteria in infected chickens can be reduced in a significant number of the birds by 99.9 percent for a cost of pennies a day, said <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> biochemist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLoach </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, College Station, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> DeLoach </PERSON> said in a report issued here by the agency that lactose and D-mannose were added to the drinking water of chicks dosed with 100 million Salmonella typhirmurium bacteria. When the 10-day-old chicks were compared with birds that had received the bacteria but no sugars, only 53 percent of the birds on lactose and only 26 percent of those on D-mannose had any salmonella bacteria, he said. `` It's not only important how many birds had salmonella, but how many salmonella bacteria those birds had,'' <PERSON> DeLoach </PERSON> said. `` The birds treated with either mannose or lactose had 99.9 percent fewer salmonella than the control birds in those experiments.'' <PERSON> DeLoach </PERSON> added: `` Lactose worked just as well as mannose, and the cost of lactose in drinking water might be no more than two cents per bird. Right now, if the poultry producer put his birds on D-mannose for 10 days, it would cost him 50 cents a bird.'' The exact amount of bacterial contamination in poultry is unclear, but <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> and private estimates have ranged from 35 percent to 60 percent nationally. Salmonella and other organisms can be spread when slaughtered birds are put through eviscerating machines and their intestinal contents are spilled. <PERSON> DeLoach </PERSON> was part of a team studying salmonella at the agency's veterinary toxicology research unit at College Station D-mannose is produced naturally by the Fraxinus ornus plant along the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> basin </LOCATION>, the report said. The sugar _ seminose and carubinose _ is available commercially in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A sister compound, mannitol, has been used for years as a stabilizer and preservative in pharmaceutical products. The report said D-mannose reduces the ability of salmonella bacteria to settle in a chicken's intestines, forcing the organisms to pass harmlessly out of the bird. Studies are still under way on how lactose works.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
