<HEAD>USDA Using Soil Volunteers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of volunteers are being used to help farmers comply with new federal conservation requirements, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. A record 8,222 volunteers helped the department's <ORGANIZATION> Soil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in the 1988 fiscal year that ended last Sept. 30, almost a four-fold increase from 2,223 the previous year. Wilson Scaling, chief of the agency, said the unpaid helpers will be recognized during National Volunteer Week, April 9-15. `` We're in the midst of one of the biggest conservation efforts in history, and volunteers andre playing a key role,'' he said. Scaling referred to provisions in the 1985 farm law requiring farmers with highly erodible crop land to have a conservation plan approved by the agency no later than Dec. 31, 1989, and to have it implemented by Dec. 31, 1994. The volunteers, called the Earth Team by the agency, include college students to retired people. They're used for a variety of jobs, including design and layout of conservation practices on individual farms, educational activities, and computer and general office assistance. Scaling said anyone interested in joining the program can call a toll-free number, 1-800-THE SOIL to find out more information, or they can contact local <ORGANIZATION> SCS </ORGANIZATION> offices, which are located in nearly all counties.
