<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill-Glance     03-27 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Glance,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a look at some other major oil spills and their effects.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FRANCE-AMOCO CADIZ</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The 220,000-ton tanker <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadiz </ORGANIZATION>, owned by a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, ran aground March 16, 1978, after tow lines snapped, impaling the vessel on rocks two miles off the western French coast. At least 68 million gallons of light Gulf crude oil spilled out along about 100 miles of <LOCATION> Brittany </LOCATION> coastline. The spill created an oil slick 18 miles wide and 80 miles long, blackened beaches, and killed thousands of birds and millions of sea creatures. Local industries such as tourism, fishing, and particularly the oyster industry, were seriously affected. The French government has paid out as much as $ 100 million in clean-up costs and compensation to those affected by the spill. In February, a judge recommended a $ 115.2 million judgment against <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, with the French government slated to recieve $ 44.4 million and affected towns about $ 7.5 million. Today, <PERSON> Brittany </PERSON>'s beaches are again clean, the fishermen are at work again and the oyster beds productive. But insidious damages, like the death of small animals which other fish had fed from, have caused the gradual disappearance of certain species, and officials say the total fallout from the pollution has not yet been evaluated.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NANTUCKET-ARGO MERCHANT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The Argo Merchant, a Liberian tanker, was lost in the early morning darkness on Dec. 15, 1976, when it ran onto a shoal off <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Winds and waves battered the ship while the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> tried to save it. The tanker leaked oil until it finally broke apart nine days later and lost the rest of its cargo. A total of 7.6 million gallons of residual oil -LRB- not crude -RRB- were spilled. Winds were blowing offshore, and the oil drifted into the open ocean. A few months later, no oil could be found on the ocean bottom. No serious harm to the waters or fish were detected. In 1980, a federal court ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> Argo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> was an unsafe ship, citing general mismanagement, neglect, and navigation errors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PACIFIC NORTHWEST-BARGE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Approximately 231,000 gallons of heavy bunker oil spilled from a barge off the southwest <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> coast on Dec. 22, 1988, after the tug towing the barge struck it while maneuvering to secure a towing line. The spill fooled officials, who predicted it would be broken up in heavy seas. However, a few days after the accident, a storm pushed the oil back toward land, where it washed up on hundreds of miles of beaches, including pristine wilderness beaches in Olympic National Park and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s Pacific Rim National Park. A massive cleanup effort followed, involving professional and volunteer crews. Still, up to 10,000 birds died and effects of the pollution will linger for years. The <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> company whose tug was towing the barge, <ORGANIZATION> Sause </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Towing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to pay cleanup costs. The state's cost to date is $ 350,000, of which <ORGANIZATION> Sause </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> has paid $ 115,000 A marine resource damage-assessment team is investigating the spill's effects on everything from surf smelt and sea otters, to subsistence seafood harvesting by Indian tribes. A price tag will be put on the whole package, including a cost per dead bird and for such ephemeral items as lost recreational opportunities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
