<HEAD>Yeltsin Victory Proves Popularity, Not Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> completed a stunning political comeback with his landslide victory over a candidate who symbolized power and prestige. Yet, his broad base of political support translates to little real power in his bid to challenge the government and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> bureaucracy. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> rolled up more than 89 percent of the vote to defeat technocrat <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON> for a seat representing all of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in Sunday's first multicandidate national balloting in 70 years of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> power. Together with the defeats of high-ranking officials in other areas of the country, it is a warning of popular discontent with entrenched officials and their privileges. The victory restored the burly, 58-year-old Sverdlovsk native to a place of prominence in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, giving the onetime protege of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> a parliamentary seat representing the city he used to run as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief. But it is only one of 2,250 seats in a body that meets once a year to elect a president and a new, more active legislative body: the Supreme Soviet. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said he wants all members of the congress to serve one year of their five-year terms in the Supreme Soviet, but there is no guarantee when <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> will be elected to the practically full-time lawmaking body. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> has been on the outs politically since losing his job in November 1987 following his blunt criticism of the party's style of leadership and warnings of a Stalin-like cult developing around <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. During his populist campaign against the privileges of the party elite and the failure of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms to put food on the tables of ordinary people, however, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was careful not to challenge <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s leadership. He repeated that disclaimer after his victory. `` I did n't consider myself, I do n't consider myself, and I do n't want to be an alternative candidate to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told hundreds of workers Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, where he serves as first deputy chairman Accused in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of advocating a multiparty system, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> has denied the charge and said it was an effort to undermine his campaign. But he gave a clue about how he plans to push his program, saying deputies must form interest groups if they expect to accomplish anything. `` It is impossible to carry out 2,250 programs, as many as there are deputies,'' he said Monday. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said he foresaw `` some based on ecology, some on social issues, some on the economy. In this way they can be formed to strengthen that trend, that voice.'' `` And just the opposite, they can stand as a strong barrier against those trends that people do n't need, which hurt our people and the government too,'' he said. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> ran hard in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s most visible electoral district against what he said is an entrenched power structure that enjoys special privileges while creating shortages for the masses by mismanaging the economy. He said the leadership has failed to meet its top priority of improving living conditions because reforms have not gone far enough. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> campaigned for eliminating most government ministries and cutting the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> bureaucracy to improve local autonomy. His campaign was built on his popularity gained while serving as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Communist Party chief in 1985-87. It also served as a lightning rod for discontent that is surfacing as Soviets are increasingly allowed to voice their opinions. <PERSON> Yevgeniya </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonkonovye </PERSON>, 62, said Sunday that she voted for <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> because he visited the clinic where she worked and because he used public transportation. `` You feel his earthiness,'' she said. <PERSON> Brakov </PERSON>, in contrast, came across less naturally and recited a campaign program that closely followed mainstream <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> calls for improved food and consumer goods. In his short term as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party chief, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was a close supporter of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, especially of his calls for greater openness. But it was <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> who criticized his one-time protege for being overly ambitious and presided over the meeting at which <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was fired. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> has criticized <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s electoral reforms as not being democratic enough, and he chastised the party for nominating 100 candidates for an equal number of seats in the congress. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was among the 100. In contrast, three-quarters of the 1,500 congress members chosen Sunday had competition. `` Democracy in society has gotten ahead of democracy in the party, judging by the election law,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s popularity with a program that criticized Communist Party policies could conceivably help <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, and the Soviet leader appeared to acknowledge that in comments he made to correspondents after voting Sunday. Asked about the charges made against <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> in the final days of the campaign, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the former <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party leader must be willing to accept criticism along with everyone else in a freer atmosphere. But he also said those who supported <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s attacks on bureaucracy were ardent supporters of continuing reforms. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> might be able to use the strong showing by <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> and losses suffered by conservatives elsewhere to show the conservatives still in the power structure thatay \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 88.50 \* \* \* Jul \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 87.00 \* \* \* Sep \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 84.25 \* \* \* Dec \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 82.25 \* \* \* Jan \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* Mar \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* May \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* Jul \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* Sep \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* Dec \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* Jan \* # \* \* # \* \* # \* 78.75 \* \* \* Fri.'s open int 145.
