<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     03-27 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronauts Ready For First Space Shuttle Planetary Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The astronauts who will fly the first space shuttle planetary mission said Monday the <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> probe they are to launch toward <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> next month could teach us about more than that hot planet. `` Not only will we learn much about <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> but we'll learn more about Earth'' and why these neighboring planets evolved so differently, said astronaut <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Thagard </PERSON>. Astronaut <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Grabe </PERSON>, who will pilot the shuttle Atlantis, noted that <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> will be the first American planetary launch in 12 years and the first from the shuttle. `` The planetary program has been dormant for some time,'' he said. `` So <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> will be a very fullfilling flight for us. Not only when we launch it, but 15 months later when it orbits <PERSON> Venus </PERSON>.'' Astronaut <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who will command the flight, said the <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> flight is a `` logical marriage between the manned and unmanned space programs.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> and his four Atlantis crew members held a news conference to discuss the four-day flight, scheduled for launch from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, on April 28. Six hours after Atlantis lifts off, astronauts <PERSON> Thagard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> are to release the <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> spacecraft from the cargo bay. An hour later, a payload rocket motor is to ignite to start the 8,000-pound probe on a 466-day voyage to <PERSON> Venus </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> is to reach <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> on Aug. 10, 1990, swooping into orbit to begin 243 days of mapping the entire surface of the planet with high-resolution radar. `` Venus is our closest neighbor in terms of space, mass and size,'' <PERSON> Thagard </PERSON> said. `` Planetary science is very important to learning how the Earth evolved and what is going on here. <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> is another data point. We worry about the greenhouse effect here on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> could tell us if there are any parallels between <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Venus </PERSON>.'' Although Earth and <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> were almost identical at the beginning of the solar system, some 4.6 billion years ago, they evolved very differently. Today, <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> has a surface temperature of 900 degrees and is shrouded in a cloudy atmosphere. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleave </PERSON>, a mission specialist on next month's mission, said <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION>'s radar images could show whether <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> has shifting crustal plates similar to those that sometimes cause earthquakes. `` Being a civil engineer and interested in the design of buildings that could withstand earthquakes, I would like to know more about plate tectonics,'' she said. `` Because there is no water on <PERSON> Venus </PERSON>, the radar can look at the entire planet and this might help us understand plate tectonics on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> also could answer questions about the extent of volcanic activity on <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> and whether the planet ever had oceans.
