<HEAD>New York City Reins In Pit Bulls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city is getting tough on the pugnacious pit bull dog, barring the breed from taking up future residence and requiring photos and tattoos of those already here. The <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> adopted a Health Code amendment Monday that requires that all pit bull terriers be registered, spayed or neutered and identified by photographs and tattooing. The regulations, which go into effect in 30 days, also require that the animals be muzzled whenever there is any potential contact with the public, that they be on a leash when outside the owner's home and that signs be posted on the premises indicating the presence of a pit bull The terriers, which were long ago bred to battle bulls for sport, have been known to turn on humans without warning and bite or maul them. Registration of all pit bulls with the city <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> must take place before Oct. 1, and owners must have proof of liability insurance of at least $ 100,000. Unregistered pit bulls can be seized and owners face fines of up to $ 500 a day, said department spokesman <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON>. `` After October first,'' he said, `` there will be no pit bulls allowed into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. ... Eventually, there will come a time when there will be no pit bulls in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Adkins </PERSON> said the only figures he had available on deaths from dog attacks indicated that from 1983 to August 1987, there were 29 deaths nationally and 21 of those were caused by pit bulls.
