 A gene and data bank for shrubs and other woody landscape plants has been established at the National Arboretum, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Arboretum director <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON> said plant researchers and nurseries will use the bank to find and obtain landscape specimens at other arboretums and nurseries around the country _ as well as in the National Arboretum. <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON> also said collections of plants at the 444-acre arboretum will be expanded as part of a new national woody landscape plant repository. A new computer bank will make it easier to develop new and better specimens. The new repository is the first of its kind at the national level, he said. The arboretum is operated by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON> said public interest in gardening has expanded rapidly since 1978, including an increase of almost a third in the sales of landscape plants. Those sales were estimated at more than $ 7 billion last year.
