 faith or malice here on our part, the law is clear that a lawsuit like that could be successfully defended,'' he said, adding such a lawsuit could be considered frivolous by the courts. The <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> report on pesticide residues in childrens' food was released in late February, and concluded that eating apples treated with the growth regulator Alar increased cancer risk in children. The report has been widely disputed, and the federal government has said apples are safe to eat. The industry has accused the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> of unfairness because only 5 percent of the crop is treated with Alar. Alar is the trade name for daminozide, and is still legal to use. Nevertheless, the report caused an uproar, prompting some school districts to temporarily ban apples, hurting exports and retail sales. The exact economic impact has not yet been measured, but prices for the top grade of red apples have dropped about $ 2 per box in recent weeks, and apple shipments from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> dropped by over 300,000 boxes in the past two weeks. Warehouses in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which produces half the nation's supermarket apples, still have 17.7 million boxes of red apples from the fall harvest in storage Multiplying that by $ 2 per 42-pound box produces an economic loss of $ 35.4 million for the rest of the season, even if prices drop no further. `` The basic problem in the industry now is they've -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- smeared the red apple so bad on the Alar thing that it's rolling over into the non-Alar-treated fruit,'' <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON> said. `` Everytime a housewife sees red apples she could be seeing red herself,'' he said. `` I do n't know how you can measure that.''
