<SECOND>AM-Bearings-Dumping,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Imports Being Sold in U.S. at Less than Fair Value</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it had made a final determination that imports of anti-friction bearings from nine countries are being sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at less than fair value. The department's ruling covered imports from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>. The agency also ruled that bearings from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> were being subsidized. As a result of earlier preliminary rulings in the case, cash deposits or bonds are being imposed on imports from the nine countries to offset the price advantages and subsidies. If the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> makes a final ruling that the low-priced imports harm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will instruct the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to collect the final anti-dumping and countervailing duties. The department began its investigation after the <ORGANIZATION> Torrington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Torrington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, filed a petition last March on behalf of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bearing industry, alleging that massive dumping by the foreign countries was damaging the domestic bearing industry. <LOCATION> Torrington </LOCATION> is the nation's largest producer of a range of bearings. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gridley </PERSON>, the company's industry marketing manager, said several studies had found that a `` substantial number of bearing factories closed and workers were laid off while at the same time imports from these foreign countries have been increasing.'' <PERSON> Gridley </PERSON> said the company was very pleased with the ruling and with the department's in-depth inquiry. The petition resulted in 34 anti-dumping and 10 countervailing duty investigations covering several kinds of bearings. The department said the investigations were the most technical and complex in several years, and covered more than 25 foreign companies. Imports of anti-friction bearings from the nine countries were estimated at about $ 650 million in 1988. Anti-friction bearings are used in the aircraft, automotive, machinery and electronics industries.
