yel </PERSON> named <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> to lead an interim government Sept. 22, when <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> could not agree on a successor at the end of <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s six-year term. Moslems supported by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> swore allegiance to <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, the incumbent Sunni Moslem premier, and two governments resulted. Under an unwritten agreement dating to independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1943, the president is a Christian, the premier a Sunni and the parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> says the Syrians have become an occupation force by taking sides, and has declared a `` war of liberation'' to drive them out. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> contends the Syrian military presence is legitimate. `` The Syrian army entered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1976 at the request of the ... Lebanese government,'' he told reporters. `` This request was later endorsed by the Arab League, of which <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is a founding member.'' Any demand for Syrian withdrawal should come from a united government, `` which is not present at the moment,'' he said, and accused <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> of `` pushing <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to the brink of ... disaster.''
