secretary. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government released contradictory findings in the 1984 assassination of Premier <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> Monday, one implicating her personal secretary and expressing the suspicion that he was linked to the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>. A memorandum accompanying this report exonerated the secretary, said Home Minister <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> in releasing the report to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> disclosed at the same time that separate investigations that did not figure in the report `` unraveled a conspiracy, a larger conspiracy to eliminate Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>,'' and that more arrests were expected shortly Two Sikh bodyguards shot and killed Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> on Oct. 31, 1984, as she walked through the garden of her <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> residence to a television interview. Her son, <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON>, replaced her as prime minister. A report by an investigative commission under <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> M.P. <PERSON> Thakkar </PERSON> was completed nearly three years ago, but was kept secret on national security grounds. This inquiry ran parallel to an inquiry of police experts called the Special Investigating Team. The 314-page Thakkar report implicated <PERSON> Rajendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s secretary for more than 20 years, and also said security officials were aware of the threat to Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s life and could have prevented the murder. A memorandum accompanying the report said the allegations were checked out by the Special Investigating Team, appointed by the government to lay charges against those involved, and it found <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> had `` no hand in the conspiracy.'' <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> the team completed its work in January and added that charges will be filed soon against others involved in the conspiracy. The Thakkar report links only three people directly to the assassination: the two known gunmen and <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON>, 52, left government after the assassination, but returned last month as an adviser to <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> could not be reached at his home or office for comment, but the government has said he is innocent. According to the Thakkar report, Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> reprimanded <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> a month before her death and made inquiries about replacing him. It accused <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> of facilitating the murder by countermanding an order to remove all Sikhs from the inner security circle, approving shift changes for one assassin, and keeping secret instructions about Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s security that indicated `` he was snooping or spying on the late prime minister and was active as an informant for someone.'' The report said <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> was walking with Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to the interview, but fell back just before the shooting started. `` It appears that he has been making a deliberate effort to emphasize that he had not noticed <PERSON> Beant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> taking out his revolver from his hip pocket,'' the report said. It said <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> lied or gave inadequate reponses to questions about entries in his diary about one assassin, foreign money, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and his association with a Sikh suspected of having ties to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agency, which `` gives rise to a suspicion as to whether <PERSON> Dhawan </PERSON> had some links with the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>.'' The Thakkar report said security officials `` appear to have taken things for granted.'' It said `` high officials ... were aware of the threat to the life of the prime minister'' and that `` the unfortunate occurrence could have been averted'' through careful study and precautionary action. <PERSON> Thakkar </PERSON> finished his report in February 1986, but recommended it be kept secret lest its contents jeopardize other investigations. Only <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and two senior <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers had seen the report when <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> passed a resolution in July 1986 allowing it to be withheld. Two weeks ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> newspaper published excerpts and oppostion lawmakers demanded the report be released. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> made it public after some members of his <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said they would do it if he did not. The government says Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was killed in revenge for an army raid she ordered in June 1984 on <LOCATION> Sikhdom </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, to clear the compound of militants. At least 1,200 people died, most of them Sikhs. Other bodyguards shot and killed one assassin, <PERSON> Beant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, and the other, <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, was convicted of murder and hanged on Jan. 6. A third Sikh, <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, was convicted of conspiracy and hanged. The three men were not related. All male Sikhs take the name <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, which means lion.
