<SECOND>AM-TMI-Kemeny,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman Of Presidential TMI Panel Praises Nuke Industry Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-TMI Remembered, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the presidential commission that investigated the Three Mile Island accident said Monday that the nuclear power industry apparently has heeded the panel's recommendations and become more safety conscious `` We warned them that unless they changed their attitude completely they would be out of business, and it sounds to me as if they took it to heart,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said on the eve of the 10th anniversary of the nation's worst atomic power accident. <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> president, based his assessment on a recent report by the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION>, a group the industry established after <ORGANIZATION> Three </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> to work on safety issues. The institute concluded that the nation's 111 nuclear power plants now licensed are safer and more efficient. `` I'm not saying that every problem has been fixed,'' <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said in an interview. But he said it was `` very hard for me to believe that it's the same industry we really tore apart 10 years ago.'' Still, <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said he was concerned that the Nuclear Regulatory Commission may have become even more mired in a maze of regulations that do n't necessarily insure safety. Referring to reports that the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> mandated 149 changes based on his commission's recommendations, <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said: `` That's typical madness to me. I wish they had mandated 40 important -LRB- changes -RRB-. They'd have a much better chance of compliance.'' <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON>, 62, is a mathematician who had a small role in the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Project that developed the first atomic bomb during World War II, and who later worked as a research assistant to <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>. President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> to head a 12-member commission to investigate the Three Mile Island accident. The panel spent six months investigating the March 28, 1979, partial meltdown at the nuclear power plant in <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. Among its recommendations that the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> adopted were establishing 10-mile evacuation-planning zones around commercial reactors and requiring an array of new control-room equipment to better apprise operators of a plant's safety status. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., charged during the weekend that nearly four out of five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> atomic plants still have failed to complete all the changes <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> did not dispute <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>'s allegations, but reached a different conclusion, noting an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> official's statement that more than 97 percent of the changes have been completed. `` Remember, these are all changes, none of which were in place 10 years ago,'' <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said. `` I think that's substantial change.'' Ten years ago <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> called the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> `` the worst government agency that existed.'' He said he still has concerns. `` What we found -LRB- then -RRB- was that they had such a huge number of regulations _ they regulated everything, even minute things _ that many -LRB- nuclear plant officials -RRB- ... spent all their time making sure that they met all the regulations, rather than worrying whether their plant was safe,'' <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said. `` I do n't mean that those two things are inconsistent, but just because you meet all the paper regulations does not mean your plant is safe.'' <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said he has n't followed the commission closely in recent years, but noted that the private <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> duplicates much of the information sharing, inspection and training that the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> does, sometimes with stricter standards. `` To me that's a suggestion that the industry itself feels that the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> is not sufficient,'' <PERSON> Kemeny </PERSON> said. `` Let me say one thing for the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>,'' he added. `` I do n't think regulation alone can solve this problem. Unless the industry has a commitment to safety, no amount of regulation can solve it.''
