<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas released an empty railroad car parked at a siding Monday, and the car killed three people as it rumbled down the tracks for nine miles before coming to a halt, officials reported. <ORGANIZATION> Enafer </ORGANIZATION>, the state railroad company, said the car was set loose near <LOCATION> Chosica </LOCATION>, 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. It blamed left-wing rebels but did not name a specific group. The brief statement did not identify the three people who were killed or give any other details. Officials reported two policemen were slain by gunmen of the Maoist Shining Path movement in separate attacks. They said a police captain was fatally wounded by four guerrillas who shot him as he walking to his home in <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, 140 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, Sunday night. The other policeman was slain Sunday night in a downtown market in <LOCATION> Pucallpa </LOCATION>, 235 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, according to the officials. Peruvians began receiving their mail Monday when postal service resumed after a strike for nearly two months by members of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> who sought salary increases. The government and union reached an agreement Thursday on a wage and benefit package but no details were released. About 85 percent of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s 7,000 postal employees participated in the strike that began Feb. 2 and halted home mail delivery and other services. Officials said some 10 million letters were placed in post office storerooms during the strike. The nation's 70,000 miners stayed on the job after the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATIO