 <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Santoro </PERSON>, who was considered <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s most important living composer, died of a heart attack Monday. He was 69. <PERSON> Santoro </PERSON> collapsed onstage while conducting an orchestra rehearsal in the capital, <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>, and died shortly afterwards, according to the government news agency Radiobras. <PERSON> Santoro </PERSON>, born in the western <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Manaus </LOCATION> in 1919, studied violin and composed his first symphony when he was 19. His eclectic opus of symphonies, concertos, and operas included atonal and popular works. Among his best known works was the 1943 symphony `` Impressions of a Steel Foundry.'' Considered one of the successors to renowned 20th century Brazilian composer <PERSON> Heitor </PERSON> <PERSON> Villas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lobos </PERSON>, <PERSON> Santoro </PERSON> was also among the most important authorities on contemporary Brazilian music. He was particularly well known in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where he performed and taught music in the 1960s. <PERSON> Santoro </PERSON> is survived by a wife and six children. Radiobras said the funeral date and site was not announced.
