<HEAD>Machete-Wielding Mob Attacks U.S. Missionaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with witnesses' comments on details
of accident and attack. No pickup</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ A mob with machetes attacked and seriously wounded seven <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missionaries after a pickup truck carrying the Americans accidentally ran over two Haitians, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haiti-Inter </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official put the number of Americans injured in the incident Sunday at 12, but said none was hurt seriously. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said some Americans were hospitalized and that others were treated and released. The report by independent <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haiti-Inter </ORGANIZATION> said seven Free Methodist Church missionaries were hospitalized in serious condition with multiple machete wounds after the attack, and the two Haitians suffered broken legs. The missionaries and Haitians were not immediately identified. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it was not authorized to release the missionaries' names because of the Privacy Act. The radio station said the attack occurred after the pickup truck went out of control and plowed into the Haitians, who were celebrating the Lenten season on a highway near <LOCATION> Leogane </LOCATION>, about 18 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>. Bystanders stoned the truck and set upon the missionaries with machetes, the report said. It did not say what caused the truck driver to lose control. Two witnesses told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the missionaries were saved by the arrival of a soldier, who fired a shot into the air to quiet the crowd. The man and woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said some of the missionaries also were armed and that they fired their weapons. The witnesses said they were driving home to <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Leogane </LOCATION> region when they came upon the scene. They described it as `` nightmarish.'' The truck struck the crowd, and the pedestrians interpreted that action as a deliberate attempt to harm them, the witnesses said. Bands of revelers known as `` ra-ras'' are a Lenten season tradition in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. They wander about, chanting and playing drums and bamboo trumpets. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said the Americans planned to return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Tuesday. The official did not know whether the trip was scheduled as a result of the Sunday incident.
