<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Warm air spread through the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> states on Monday, toppling temperature records and causing some spring flooding. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> were pounded by thunderstorms and hail. Tornadoes were spotted in southwest <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> during a storm that packed 70 mph winds and caused damage at a trailer park near <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON>. Hail the size of tennis balls fell amid the thunderstorms at <LOCATION> Giles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Tornado watches were in effect from east central and south central <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> to far western <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and the eastern part of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> panhandle and portions of southwest <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. An unseasonably warm air mass carried spring weather into the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and along much of the <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seaboard </LOCATION>. It was 78 degrees in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, the highest temperature there since last Oct. 1. Records for the date also were set in at least 25 other places, including <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where it was 78; <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> -LRB- 72 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Alpena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> -LRB- 65 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> -LRB- 80 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Greer </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> -LRB- 78 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> -LRB- 77 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, W.V. -LRB- 80 -RRB-; and <ORGANIZATION> Meridian </ORGANIZATION>, Miss -LRB- 85 -RRB-. The high of 80 degrees in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <L