<HEAD>Tennessee Reactor to Restart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A reactor closed for more than two years at the <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, National Laboratory can be restarted, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday. The High-Flux isotope reactor has been shut down since November, 1986, when it was found to be suffering from embrittlement of the reactor pressure vessel. The vessels become brittle when continually bombarded with atomic particles as an offshot of chain reactions. Since then, there have been more than 20 safety studies of the reactor and Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON>. <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said Monday he is convinced the operation will be safe. `` I have reviewed the work that has been done to assure the safety of this reactor and I am comfortable with the restart of the reactor,'' said <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> in a statement. The reactor is expected to be restarted within five weeks. It will be operated at 85 percent power. The reactor was constructed in 1966 and is used for research on a variety of projects.
