<FIRST>a i PM-RhodesianSoldier Adv03   03-27 0991</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rhodesian Soldier, Adv 03,1017</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs April 3 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Rhodesian Soldier Lambasts Former White Rulers in Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As a <LOCATION> Rhodesian </LOCATION> soldier, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON> believed the good were white, the evil were black and the war he fought was a noble struggle waged in the name of Christian democracy. A decade later, he is convinced the war to prevent black majority rule was immoral and looks back with shame at how he and thousands of other white Rhodesians accepted `` simplistic, jingoistic nonsense'' from their leaders. Far worse, he says his fellow whites still hold blacks in contempt and he fears they are throwing away their last chance for peace in the land now called <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. Once a member of an elite counterguerrilla force, the Grey Scouts, <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON> has written the first published reproval of the seven-year war by a former supporter of white rule. In `` White Man Black War,'' Moore-King accuses the leaders _ `` Elders,'' he calls them _ in what was the breakaway British colony of <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> of an inflexibility that led to the deaths of 1,400 whites and 27,000 blacks before the white minority gave up power under British pressure in 1978. `` These Elders valued the comfort of their lifestyles beyond the lives of their children,'' Moore-King writes in the book published by <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>'s year-old <ORGANIZATION> Baobab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was greed that sent us to war.'' The 134-page volume has caused a stir among blacks and whites who fought or lived through the conflict that ended with <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION>'s transition to independent, black-governed <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> It provoked numerous reviews in the local media, with one white lawyer saying the book `` was like peeling a scab off and seeing how well the wound was healing.'' <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON>'s unforgiving and brutal accounts of war atrocities form the basis of his scathing indictment of <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION>'s leaders. He particularly assails <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, the prime minister of <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION>, calling him the whites' `` High Priest.'' `` Mr. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, along with the farmers, businessmen, and other politicians told us that we were not fighting to persecute, oppress, or deny our black countrymen _ we killed and burned to save them from communism,'' Moore-King writes. `` The shameful part of our history is not that we were wrong, just that we were so childishly thoughtless,'' <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON> said in an interview at his modest home in <LOCATION> Ruwa </LOCATION>, about 20 miles east of <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION> -LRB- formerly <LOCATION> Salisbury </LOCATION> -RRB-, the capital. The house is off a dirt road surrounded by <PERSON> African </PERSON> <PERSON> bush </PERSON> and black neighbors. Moore-King, 36, said the book, published in December and now into its second printing, was born of anger and fear he felt after returning to his homeland in 1985 after a seven-year absence. `` I feared the whites in this country were screwing up the opportunity to live in this land,'' he said. `` They have been given a second chance in a way.'' An estimated 90,000 whites remain in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> out of the 250,000 or so in the early 1970s. `` The irony is that having lost the war, we have n't lost the lifestyle,'' Moore-King added. Most whites in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> live in spacious homes, many with swimming pools and tennis courts and cared for by black servants. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who still lives in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, said he does not intend to read `` White Man Black War'' and dismissed Moore-King as a `` crank.'' `` It seems at one time he was a great Grey Scout,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> in a telephone interview. `` Now he's turned against everything he once believed.'' Moore-King, who is bearded, broad and imposingly tall, was a sergeant in the Grey Scouts, a mounted infantry unit used as a mobile fireforce and specializing in high-speed tracking. In flowing, impressionistic style, his book recounts wanton destruction, torture and pointless massacres. Soldiers mistakenly bomb a schoolhouse in which black civilians have taken refuge, and 123 are killed. A `` nanny and two pics'' walking home late at night are gunned down by inexperienced young soldiers who mistake them for guerrillas. A black man hangs spreadeagled on a steel bed-frame while a soldier sends electric jolts through wires attached to his scrotum and a nipple. Moore-King left <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> in 1978 and wandered around <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for several years, still believing the war was a noble affair. `` I swore I was n't a racist and justified it by saying I did n't hate black people, they just were n't ready for independence,'' he said <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON>'s attitude began to shift when he went to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in the early 1980s and worked at an insurance agency on an equal basis with blacks. When he returned to <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> upon the death of his parents he feared retaliation by the black government. Instead, he said, he was welcomed back by blacks who treated him with respect. But he found attitudes little changed among whites. In his book, <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON> tells of a moment soon after his return when his landlord found him sharing tea on his porch with a black neighbor. Not only were Moore-King and his wife evicted, but the landlord locked the vegetable garden Moore-King had left to his black friend. The book paints the pitiful scene of the hungry black man looking longingly through a fence at tomatoes rotting on the vine. `` It was one of a number of things that I thought were repugnant morally, but also dangerous and stupid the way anger was being stirred up in blacks,'' said <PERSON> Moore-King </PERSON>, who plans soon to leave his job as a <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION> insurance agent to work on his second book. `` I can understand now why our countrymen took up arms against us,'' he wrote in his first book. `` And if these actions and attitudes and forms of selective ignorance displayed by my tribe once caused blood and fire to spread across the land called <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION>, what will these same actions and attitudes and forms of selective ignorance produce in this land called <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs April 3</NOTE>
