<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: American Exhibit, Adv 29,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, March 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Galeries Lafayette Salutes The United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At a time when the French are trying to whip up enthusiasm for the 200th anniversary of their Revolution, visitors will be treated to an American exhibition in <LOCATION> Galeries </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s best-known department store. A major art exhibition will form the backbone of the show in the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> store, which also includes a Tex-Mex restaurant, a demonstration of Navajo arts and crafts and phone booths offering free three-minute phone calls to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The exhibition might be dubbed the biggest `` show and sell,'' gambit ever attempted in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> because it's also a commercial enterprise aimed at selling thousands of items `` made in the U.S.A.'' `` We feel the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was the most obvious choice for our annual show devoted to a foreign country,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Girardin </PERSON>, director of promotions and sales. He pointed out that people in both countries battled for liberty in the late l8th century, and that the <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafayette </PERSON>, a French statesman, had championed the American patriots' cause as a general under <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> in the American Revolutionary War. <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>'s gesture was viewed suspiciously by the French, who first condemned him but finally welcomed him back as a hero in 1781 when they saw how he'd defeated their arch-enemies, the English. The exhibition of 50 American paintings from the <ORGANIZATION> Wadsworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atheneum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, is the most important such show sponsored by a retailer in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` Chosen by the museum's curator, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> McCaughy </PERSON>, the paintings will cover the chief periods of art in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Galeries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lafayette </ORGANIZATION>. Insured for $ 50 million, the canvases will range from the works of the scenic <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> to the abstract expressionism of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> and the pop art of <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>. Also on show will be <LOCATION> Whistler </LOCATION>'s `` Coast of <LOCATION> Brittany </LOCATION>,'' as well as <ORGANIZATION> Winslow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homer </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Boy in a Dory,'' <PERSON> Georgia </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s upside down painting of <PERSON> D.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>'s pine tree and an impressionistic landscape of Etretat, a beach in <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION>, by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Inness </PERSON>. `` This will be a new kind of audience for an art show,'' said <PERSON> Girardin </PERSON>, intimating that these casual visitors would have fewer preconceived ideas than the usual culture vultures at art exhibitions. Bound to be a crowd-pleaser are 16 vintage cars contributed by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to be placed on the rooftop terrace. Long queues are expected for the first week of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> phone-booth exhibit, when free phone calls to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be offered from 2 p.m. to 6 p.m. as part of a credit-card promotion. Navajos from <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, will be on hand in their workshop-boutique to demonstrate how they weave rugs, make pottery and silver jewelry. And elsewhere, professional seamstresses will demonstrate the fine art of making a quilt. Skateboard demonstrations by Californians are expected to knock'em off their feet, if the <ORGANIZATION> Harley-Davidson </ORGANIZATION> motorcycle exhibit does n't first. And a French cactus buff will show off new breeds of the prickly succulent. While the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> restaurant from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' <LOCATION> Les </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Halles </LOCATION> district serves up chili con carne, gastronomes may also sample treats at the `` typically American'' food shop. The eclectic food selection will either fascinate Gallic gourmets or send them galloping away in droves: frozen yogurt, pop corn, diet products, biologic food products, wine without alcohol and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> bourbon for kicks. The <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was to contribute cookery items considered `` indispensable to the American way of life'' including a corn popper, a milk-shaker, a dough-kneader and a hot dog cooker. Fashions, home furnishings, accessories and leisure products will complete the vast show. Designer styles will be from Paris-based <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>, <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tahari </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuville </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Max </PERSON>. French couture will make a cameo appearance on about 20 models fashioned by top designers for Barbie dolls. The Saks boutique will not only show and sell red-white-blue socks and beach robes, but offer chocolate c