<HEAD>EAGLESWOOD TOWNSHIP, N.J.: their property.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Newsletters from the <ORGANIZATION> Pinelands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Landowners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> accused the state of `` trying to preserve land by essentially confiscating it ... Meanwhile, taxes continue to be paid by landowners held hostage by the plan.'' Researchers continue to study the Pinelands' fragile ecosystem, right down to the rare Pine Barrens tree frog and the curly grass fern. Medical research also has been conducted in the Pinelands. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Squibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> microbiologists announced that a new family of microbiotics could be developed from Pinelands soil. But for all the <ORGANIZATION> Pinelands </ORGANIZATION>' beauty and benefits, it is overshadowed as a tourist destination by the popular shore region and relatively few people take advantage of the reserve. Scattered through the scenic Pinelands are attractions such as the historic <LOCATION> Batsto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, a preserved iron-making facility, and a host of hiking trails and rivers for canoeing. `` I do n't think there is enough of an understanding in the state as to what the Pinelands means and how important it is,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> says. `` Most people think it's just a boring, flat landscape.'' Although the <ORGANIZATION> Pinelands </ORGANIZATION>' significance may not be widely and fully appreciated, and its preservation fought by some, the <ORGANIZATION> Pinelands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Does </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanya </ORGANIZATION> have any advice for her sister? `` Stay in school and do n't have kids until you finish school.'' <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a 17-year-old graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rockaway </LOCATION>, says the pregnant teen-agers she knows `` really do n't understand that once that baby's born, it's going to be hard to feed them and clothe them and take'em places and stuff like that. And that they ca n't really do the things that they used to do.'' But when asked if she used birth control, she said, `` Sometimes, but not really. No. But I'm supposed to start on it soon. But not now.'' <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Trieller </PERSON>, the clinical nurse specialist at <LOCATION> Woodmere </LOCATION>, says that kind of carelessness is common among teen-agers of every stripe. `` In the last five years, with the media talking about herpes and AIDS, adults are being more careful about sex,'' she says. `` It's not affecting the adolescent population because they think they're omnipotent. That's their modus operandi: ` I'm not going to get pregnant. I'm not going to get VD.''' <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stream </LOCATION> teen who learned the hard way that she was not immune to pregnancy, laments her abortioo kill a baby,'' she says, `` but I was only 17 at the time and still in school and I was working and my boyfriend was still in school at the time, and his mother never knew. She'd probably be upset if she ever found out.''
