<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Argentina Adv02-2Takes   03-27 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Argentina, Adv 02-2 Takes,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Argentina _ The Long Fall from Riches</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 To look at <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> is to look at a nation that has everything going for it. But nothing is. This is one of a series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the economic, social and political turbulence that has turned <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> into a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By ED McCULLOUGH</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The way things are today, it is hard to believe that after World War II <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> was one of the wealthiest nations in the world. Many Argentines today date the steady decline of their economic fortunes since then to a day in February, 1946, when Gen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> visited the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> after being elected president and came out marveling at the pile of gold bars he saw inside. `` You can hardly walk through the corridors,'' he remarked. Argentines still cite those words in looking back. They still have as high a standard of living as anyone in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, but they no longer are rich and many blame that on <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> and his policies which still exerting influence long after his heyday and 14 years after his death. He nationalized industries, regulated wages and prices and work conditions, expanded public employment and social welfare programs, convinced millions of Argentines that big government was best. He created a political party that bears his name to carry out his vision. Today, one worker of every six is employed by the government _ about 2 million overall in a population of 30 million. The state subsidizes an estimated 300 companies. The budget usually is in deficit. Natural resources go untapped. Private industry chafes at myriad regulations. `` The state, from 1945 to now, has gotten a little bigger every year, and it has long since reached the point where it can be sustained,'' says <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cresto </PERSON>, chairman of the department of economics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Buenos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aires </ORGANIZATION>. `` Everyone realizes what the problem is, but there is no general agreement on a solution,'' says <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Szewach </PERSON>, chief economist at the independent <ORGANIZATION> Latin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. The dominance of the state has been one constant in a political and economic maelstrom that has hampered development in a country blessed with resources. Over the years, soldiers ousted civilians and democratic rule gave way to dictatorship. The political and economic `` rules of the game'' changed quickly and often. New regimes have tried to wipe out what came before rather than build on what may have been achieved. Economically, currency-exchange rates have been undervalued and then overvalued. Business has been protected and then forced to face international competition. Wages and prices have been controlled and then set by market forces. Exports have been favored and then imports, agriculture and then industry. Meanwhile, the country slipped into decline _ despite fertile cropland and a temperate climate, rich fishing grounds, abundant deposits of oil, natural gas and uranium, rivers that can be tapped for hydroelectric power, and a literate population not divided by language, religion or race. The gross domestic product has stagnated at about $ 80 billion for a decade. Annual per capita income dropped to the equivalent of $ 1,630 in 1988 from $ 1,990 in 1980, according to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, 62, an attorney and human rights leader, has been president since December 1983. Already, he has outlasted all his predecessors since <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>, but his tenure has been rocky. The military, which unseated <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> in 1955, <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Frondizi </PERSON> in 1962, <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Illia </PERSON> in 1966 and the widow <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> in 1976, has had minor revolts in its ranks three times in the past two years. Human rights groups and other critics maintain the military is agitating again for political power. The radical left also has not given up, despite the brutal crackdown on subversives beginning with <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>'s government in 1974 and carried on by the 1976-83 military regime in which at least 8,963 Argentine civilians were arrested, never seen again and presumed executed, according to the findings of a commission set up by <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. But human rights groups, among them <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, estimate the number of people who disappeared _ `` desaparecidos'' _ at 10,000 to 30,000. Few expect any outbreak of violence such as that recently in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, but if it happens the spark might come from an economy that neither soldiers nor civilians have been able to control. Inflation has been at triple-digit rates in 13 of the past 14 years _ climbing from 24.39 percent in 1974 to 688 percent in 1984 and down to 387.70 percent last year. Unemployment and under-employment stand at a combined 14 percent. The austral currency is devalued every month, and wages often fail to keep up with inflation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
