<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Argentina, Adv 02-1st add,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>BUENOS AIRES: with inflation.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Looming over everything is the nearly $ 59-billion foreign debt, for which there is almost nothing to show. The military borrowed heavily to balance the budget in the late 1970s. It also used the money to buy military equipment, build highways through <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, subsidize military-run industries and inject money into chronically inefficient state-owned companies. It used some of the money to play host to the World Soccer Cup tournament in 1978. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> has borrowed mostly to pay the interest on the debt but, by his own admission, has paid only 50 percent of the interest due. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s international credit rating now is classified as `` substandard'' and is on the verge dropping to `` value impaired'' because of noncompliance with interest payments. Debt repayment now costs $ 6 billion a year and consumes _ or would if the government paid it _ more than one-half of total export earnings. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is $ 2.5 billion in arrears. In human terms, people who used to drive to work now take the bus or subway. Home ownership for many is out of the question. Vacations are shorter and closer to home. University graduates are emigrating in increasing numbers to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Wage strikes by public employees are common and schoolchildren stay home, mail does n't get delivered, businesmen go to work in car pools. The General Labor Confederation has staged 13 general strikes since <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> became president. The 4-million-member confederation, which was forged by <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>, is lending considerable support to the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s candidate, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, in the presidential elections set for May 14. Perhaps <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s biggest accomplishment has been to hold together a fragile democracy and fractious republic for five years. A main goal, he has said, is to hand over political power to an elected successor in December. That has not happened since 1928. The biggest failure of <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s military predecessor was the war with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> over the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, the Malvinas to Argentines. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s biggest failure has been the economy. He has tried without much success to cut the federal budget, reorganize the banking sector, lower trade barriers, increase tax collections and sell the state telephone company and the national airline, <ORGANIZATION> Aerolineas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Argentinas </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s second major anti-inflation plan collapsed in February. In the weeks since, the austral has plummeted by 59 percent against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. Cars valued in australs now seem half-priced to those with dollars. Apartments selling for dollars doubled in cost for buyers with australs. National elections raise the prospect of more instability. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, the front-runner, pledges to dramatically improve workers wages and hints he might not continue payments on the foreign debt. He talks vaguely of a `` productive revolution'' to spur growth and a `` social pact'' to resolve tensions. His main challenger, <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON> of <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, pledges to balance the budget, attract foreign investment and sell off state companies despite the opposition of unions. Compounding matters, the election could wind up in the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where conservative third-party candidate <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON> may hold the votes to push one or the other _ probably <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON> _ past the required 50 percent of 600 electors. In a recent television interview, <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON>, 75, said his grandchildren asked him whether they should study for a career in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, or emigrate. `` I told them they should go abroad,'' he said. A return to the days of the 1920s and 1930s, when beef and grain exports to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> propelled <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> into the top 10 countries in per capita income, is beyond anyone's hope now.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 2</NOTE>
