<SECOND>BC-Haiti-Democracy, Adv 02,1130</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Six Months After Coup, Democracy Remains Elusive in Haiti</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ In a roofless, burned-out church, the congregation sings hymns in Creole about death and crushed dreams. `` They kill us in the street, they kill us in our homes, they kill us inside church.'' The words flowed from 200 or so worshipers during Mass at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the midst of slum. `` The problems of our country make us die like animals. `` Democracy. Democracy.'' In September thugs with machetes, guns and spikes stormed into <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bosco </LOCATION> during <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>, killing 13 people and wounding 70 others before setting the church afire with gasoline. A week later, on Sept. 17, rank-and-file soldiers revolted and put Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril in power. They overthrew Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> and stirred hopes for democracy at last in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. The Caribbean-island nation has known almost nothing but brutal dictatorships since winning independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1804 _ the first slave state to become a nation. Today, six months after <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> took over and three years after dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> `` Baby Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> flew to exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, there is disillusionment over the pace of promised democratic reforms, while allegations of human-rights violations continue. But <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>, who holds a law degree, has made some, albeit slow, progress toward his pled an elected government. His government maintains democracy is the only path for the poorest country in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>. `` We've had dictatorships for 184 years and we are still the least developing nation in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. So something is wrong with how we governed,'' said Foreign Minister <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> Elie </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> in an interview. `` Democracy is not a choice; it's an imperative.'' In February, <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> approved the formation of an independent council to oversee eventual elections and he recently restored 291 articles of the 1987 constitution, suspended in June by <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>. But 37 articles that mostly restricted the army's role were not revived because, <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> said, they were inconsistent with a de facto government. `` You ca n't expect this government to behave like a democratically elected government,'' sociologist <PERSON> Leopold </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlanger </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Haitian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview. `` Avril is a product of the system. `` The only thing we have to expect is that he assures a secure, fair and honest democratic process.'' The 50-year-old <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> was <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>'s close financial adviser and people still associate him with the old regime. Many charge he is making reforms merely to win back $ 70 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic assistance. The aid was frozen Nov. 29, 1987, after goonsquads killed 34 people voting in the country's first election in 30 years. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has said it wo n't renew aid until democratic government is in place but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could release some funds in the meantime as an incentive. With about 80 percent of the country's 5.5 million people living in dire poverty, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> desperately needs help. `` Witholding aid has been very negative,'' said the foreign minister. `` The social-economic factors have worsened so we can not say how these measures have in any way advanced democracy.'' This year, labor strikes and sporadic demonstrations broke out in <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>, the capital, and in the provinces with demands for <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> to step down. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Watch and other human rights groups say abuses and arbitrary arrests by the army and paramilitary groups continue to be made of people in peasant organizations, labor unions and church groups. `` The basic human rights situation has not changed,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Duval </PERSON>, who was a political prisoner under <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> and today runs a human rights group. `` In the last weeks we have found one to two bodies a night as a result of the political situation.'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>'s feared private militia, the <ORGANIZATION> Tonton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macoute </ORGANIZATION>, was disbanded after <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> fled and some were integrated into the 7,000-member army. But they were chased out by soldiers who brought <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> to power. Although disorganized, the army wields considerable power. `` You're not going to get to power if there's not a reasonable understanding with those guys,'' said presidenial hopeful <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Bazin </PERSON>, a former Finance Minister and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> economist. `` You would be killed or disappear one morning.'' Optimism waned a month after <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> took office when the soldiers who put him in power were jailed, accused of plotting a coup. Three months later, they were released. No explanation was given. But the tide turned in late December when <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Franck </PERSON> <PERSON> Romain </PERSON>, the notorious mayor of <LOCATION> Port-Au-Prince </LOCATION>, safe passage to the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, which shares the island of Hispaniola with <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Romain </PERSON>, a retired colonel, was believed to have orchestrated the church massacre and was implicated in the one against voters in 1987. `` Giving <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> safe conduct showed the tendency of the government to preserve the status quo and encourage the Duvalierists to stay on _ not to pursue the murderers of Nov. 29 or the church massacre,'' said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Dejoie </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, son of popular industrialist who lost to <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON>'s father, in the disputed 1957 election. Fears also abound that elections would again be disrupted or rigged, as was believed the case in the elections Jan. 17, 1988, when frightened voters stayed home and <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> came to power amid allegations of fraud. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> was overthrown by <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> five months later. `` International pressure would have to be great so they ca n't repeat the events of November or of January's sham election,'' said sociologist <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronceray </PERSON>, the runner-up in the 1988 election About a dozen opposition parties and an array of organizations have emerged since 1986 but are divided. `` The democratic process depends on confidence building between the army and civilians,'' a Western diplomat said. `` Civilians have to trust the army to take its role but not to take control. And you have to have the willingness of the existing government, the quietude of the far left and the tolerance of the far right.'' No one predicts what will happen. The Communist Party, the grassroots `` popular church'' and leftist unions are influential with peasants and the poor. These groups want <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> to step down and allow a coalition government to govern until elections. Many say <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> is caught in the middle. `` He risks being overthrown if he does n't make enough progress. He risks it if he does,'' said the diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` So he's trying to maintain an equilibrium.''
</TEXT>
