 `` SING'' Generations of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> high school students have enjoyed one of academia's most popular traditions, Sing. The school song and dance competition between grades at individual schools such as Erasmus Hall and <LOCATION> Midwood </LOCATION> was a joyous and spirited event. It bubbled like the 2 cents plain at <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON>'s ice cream parlor. Unfortunately, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON>'s recreation of that spirited show in `` SING'' is as flat as a stale egg cream. It was written by <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitchford </PERSON>, and has the same situational formulas as his `` Fame'' and `` Footloose.'' It stars two newcomers, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Steen </PERSON>, who are appealing enough but lack the power and talent to truly carry a movie. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasser </PERSON>, heavier and less frenzied than her `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>'' days, co-stars as <PERSON> Steen </PERSON>'s mom. <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracco </PERSON> -LRB- `` Someone to Watch Over Me'' -RRB-, with a heavy Hollywood-style <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> accent, portrays a street-tough teacher who returns to her community. Singer <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON> -LRB- `` A Soldier's Story'' -RRB- is the only cast member who has enough high energy to dominate the screen and infuse some excitement. But her explosive talent is little used in her role as a teacher who also works with the Sing committee. `` SING'' is centered around the threatened closing of an imaginary <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> high school where the competition has been a community tradition. Students, faculty and members of the neighborhood rally to keep the school open so the skits can be put on, and to retain a way of life. At the same time, a local pun