 `` The Thin Blue Line'' -LRB- HBO Home Video. VHS-Beta, $ 89.99 -RRB- <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' singular documentary about the circumstances that led to a man being convicted of murdering a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> police officer and condemned to death is at the very least harrowing in its implications. Before you say it could n't happen to you, read on: It was Thanksgiving weekend in 1976 when <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, a day laborer with no criminal record, fell in with <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a 16-year-old juvenile delinquent. They spent the day hanging out. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> says they split up at 10 p.m. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> testified that they were together at midnight, when Officer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> died during a routine traffic stop, shot to death by a gun <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> had stolen. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> boasted about killing a cop to friends, but when he fingered <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> for the crime, he was believed. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, who has maintained he is innocent, landed on death row. His sentence later was commuted to life in prison. What's harrowing is the low-key way in which <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> reconstructs the crime, offers the testimony of witnesses and conducts interviews with the principals. Very gradually you realize that <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> got railroaded by police and prosecutors with the best intentions in the world. They knew he was guilty; it was just a case of fitting the facts to conform to that truth. `` Rashomon'' this is n't, but powerful and persuasive and chilling it is. As a result of <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' critically acclaimed effort, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' conviction was overturned In December, a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> state judge recommended that <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> receiv