 `` <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> and His Large Band'' -LRB- Curb-MCA -RRB- _ <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> So besides large, just what sort of band is this? Listen to the album's instrumental opener, `` The Blues Walk,'' and you might think `` large band'' is just a clever name for 1940s `` big band.'' But wait. Next comes `` Here I Am,'' an odd comic turn combining spoken-word passages with a blues-rock refrain. Now skip ahead a few tracks and hear that unmistakable country sound. So what sort of band is this? Why, it's a jazz-blues-swing-R & amp; B-country-western-rock band, of course. And the individual songs on this fun, quirky album are just as tough to categorize. `` I Married Her Just Because She Looks Like You'' comes closest to following a standard country formula, but its wry lyrics are a cut above that standard. `` Good Intentions'' is a sort of talkin' blues number that could easily come from <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bromberg </PERSON>'s songbook Then there's `` What Do You Do,'' which starts out as a sassy blues number, turns into a bar-pickup conversation -LRB- <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> in duet with vocalist <PERSON> Francine </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> -RRB- and slides into the 1936 standard `` The Glory of Love.'' Tying all of this together is <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>'s peculiar combination of cynicism and romanticism that adds an edge to his I-love-you songs -LRB- `` I Know You Know'' -RRB- and a softness to his she-done-me-wrong songs -LRB- `` Once Is Enough'' -RRB-. This Texan's country roots come out more strongly as the album plays on. The world could do without <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>'s cover of `` Stand By Your Man,'' but his reworking of the traditional `` Farther Along'' into the lost-love ballad `` If You Were to Wake Up'' has a simple charm. As for the Large Band, it adapts to the needs of each song, appearing in various sizes and combinations of instruments including fiddles, cell