<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Apples-Chemicals Adv30   03-27 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Apples-Chemicals, Adv 30,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, March 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Apple a Day Might Make the Doctor Sick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An apple a day really might keep the doctor away _ especially if the doctor knew what went on it. If fruit were labele the label on apples would list fiber, potassium and vitamin C _ all of which are good for you. It also might list azinphis methyl, Captan, Supracide, parathion, <PERSON> Elgetol </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sevin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NAA </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NAD </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ziram </PERSON>, diphenylamine, <LOCATION> Lorsban </LOCATION> and benzimidazole. These might not be so good, but they're among the dozens of chemicals routinely used to bring apples from fruit trees to fruit bowls. Without some of them, according to <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> apple grower <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, `` People would have to get used to biting into an apple and seeing a whole or half a worm.'' Probably the best-known of these chemicals right now is Alar, the market name for daminozide, which helps apples ripen, extends shelf life and prevents bruising. Many schools pulled apples from their lunchrooms this month after the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Res </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said Alar increased the risk of cancer among children, whose diet contains proportionally more fruit than adults. Most schools let apples back in after the claim was disputed by regulators, <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the industry, which cut its use of Alar to 5 percent of the $ 1.2 billion-a-year crop since concerns were first raised in 1985. But dozens of other chemicals are routinely used, and the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> considers several of them to be cancer-causing even though, like Alar, they are legal. A recent <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> Poll found that 84.2 percent of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> would choose organically grown food if given the choice. But <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said that without the chemicals, an apple `` would be a rather small, gnarled -LRB- object -RRB- that kind of resembled an apple. It would be covered with a black fungus scab, infested with various decay molds which could have natural carcinogens. It would undoubtedly have codling bud moths and other types of larvae.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s 5,000 growers, who produce about half the nation's apples, spend an average $ 449 per acre to buy and apply chemicals each year, said <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> tree fruit extension agent Many of the chemicals have been identified as harmful to childen by the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> report, which studied chemical residues on food. But those findings are in dispute, and the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> and Surgeon General have all said apples are safe. Here is a typical chemical season for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> apples: In early April, before bloom, an organophosphate spray _ Supracide, <LOCATION> Lorsban </LOCATION> or parathion _ kills the eggs of European red mites and also controls the spread of <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scale </ORGANIZATION>, a pest which can kill trees. In May, growers will apply Guthion, the marketing name for azinphis methyl, an insecticide that kills the codling moth larva, which produces worms in apples and is the most damaging pest in the orchard. Also applied at bloom time is <PERSON> Elgetol </PERSON>, a `` thinner'' that burns off some of the flowers, reducing the number of apples a tree will bear. Untreated trees will produce huge crops one year and tiny ones the next to conserve energy. Another thinner is <PERSON> Sevin </PERSON>, an insecticide made from the chemical carbarylaced Alar as a `` stop-drop,'' which farmers would spray about a month after bloom to keep apples on trees; an apple on the ground is worthless. <ORGANIZATION> NAA </ORGANIZATION> and NAD are less effective, and there is no substitute for Alar's ability to extend shelf life, <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> said. Ziram or Captan, fungicides used to battle bull's eye rot, also are applied at this time. In warehouses, the apples are rinsed, washed with detergent, rinsed again, sometimes waxed, dried and placed in boxes for shipment. Those destined for storage for three months to a year might be treated with two chemicals. One is benzimidazole, a fungicide; the other is diphenylamine, which prevents the red skin from turning brown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for March 30</NOTE>
