<HEAD>Researcher Says Climbing Stairs Not Good Exercise For Fatties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fat people should n't climb stairs for exercise because it can put dangerous stress on their hearts, a physician says. `` Stair climbing is excellent exercise for individuals who are not overweight. However, stair climbing is not the best way for overweight people to lose weight,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Marque </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION> pulmonary specialist who tested 20 men at or near their ideal weight and 10 who were 30 percent overweight on a miniature `` escalator'' sold for exercise. `` An overweight person must perform an excessive amount of work to climb stairs even at a modest pace,'' <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> recently told the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION> for Experimental Biology. The men were tested at 40, 50, 60 and 70 steps a minute for five minutes at each speed, going without a rest from one speed to the next. Heart rates and oxygen consumption were measured throughout. Fifty steps a minute is about normal climbing speed, but only three of the fat men managed to get past 40 steps a minute, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said. `` Seven of the 10 reached exhaustion in three or four minutes at the lowest speed. The other three reached exhaustion in the next five minutes.'' Nearly all of the other group got to 60 or 70 steps a minund of a nut and a bolt. You sew on the nut part into the front of the eye, then screw the bolt in through this supporting structure,'' said <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>. One major problem, is that rejection sets in faster than many other sorts of plastic implants, he said. `` It's different than an artificial heart valve or an artificial hip, where it's totally enclosed. For the patient to see, it has to protrude partly out. And the body tries to extrude it.'' Patients must use an antibiotic ointment on the lens and eyelid at night, with a pad to protect the lens and `` close'' the eye for sleep. In the morning, they clean it off with hydrogen peroxide on a cotton swab. Some implants can last for years, but complications usually set in after a year or two.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Doctor Claims First Test For Premenstrual Syndrome</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gynecologist says he's developed a test to detect whether moodiness is a result of premenstrual syndrome, but others say his work is promising although the sample is too small to be conclusive. Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Portman </PERSON>, whose clinic in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, specializes in PMS and menopausal care, told the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Experimental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biology </ORGANIZATION> that he has found low levels of the antibody for leuteinizing hormone _ the hormone controlling ovulation _ among PMS sufferers. <PERSON> Portman </PERSON> said his is the first biological test for PMS, which is estimated to affect anywhere from one-tenth to half of all women. `` It would be wonderful if we had a test like that,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Branning </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> gynecologist. A test would help doctors convince women whose depression was not due to PMS that they needed to try other treatment. She and gynecologist <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Portman </PERSON>'s sample _ 456 women with <ORGANIZATION> PMS </ORGANIZATION> and 65 symptom-free controls _ was too small for conclusive results. `` PMS is such a very diffuse problem, it's hard to deal with. It has such protean manifestations,'' said <PERSON> Branning </PERSON>. `` I think you aways wonder if it's not more than one thing that we've lumped together under one heading.'' Symptoms include depression, distorted thinking, angry outbursts, headache, food binges and bloating in the weeks between ovulation and menstruation. Without a test, <PERSON> Portman </PERSON> said, doctors must see whether a woman's symptoms fit PMS and ask her to chart them against her period for several months `` We are at the very embryonic stage of what we have,'' said <PERSON> Portman </PERSON>. `` We have a high and statistic significant correlation of antibody levels and PMS. Hopefully, over the next few years we can unravel more of this.''
