<HEAD>Eastern Seeks New Pilots In Class, Old Ones In Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with judge setting hearing for Thursday after
meeting with lawyers; airline saying 40 pilots beginning training. No pickup.
Adds byline. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today set a hearing on a key issue in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to force its pilots back to work, while the strikebound carrier began its first class in training replacement pilots. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said this morning he would hear arguments Thursday on whether the pilots' strike was only a refusal to cross Machinists' picket lines, or was a primary strike, which could be illegal under the Railway Labor Act. The 11th <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> had asked the judge for a decision on the issue, which is central to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s legal efforts to end the 3-week-old walkout. `` As I see it, I need to make a determination whether refusal to cross the picket line is a ` pretext,''' the judge said today. `` I must determine what the appeals court means about ` pretext.''' <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Linsey </PERSON> asked for Thursday's hearing during the judge's meeting with lawyers. `` We do n't think that Eastern has shown in the previous hearings that <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>'s action was a pretext,'' <PERSON> Linsey </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> claims the Railway Labor Act gives its members the right to show sympathy for the striking Machinists. The appeals court agreed, but added that `` a claim of a sympathy strike can not be used as a pretext to shield conduct that otherwise would be a clear violation of the Railway Labor Act.'' Eastern lawyer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said today that the judge already had enough evidence, unsuccessfully arguing for <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> to immediately forward to the appeals judges the finding that the pilots' walkout was not allowed. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said the first six-week training class for about 40 replacement pilots was beginning today with an organizational session. All but 200 of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s 3,600 pilots have refused to work since the strike began March 4. `` I have heard that they're even coming from other airlines,'' <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said of the new pilots. `` They're coming over because they can make seniority faster.'' Eastern has been operating only about 10 percent of its daily pre-strike schedule of 1,040 flights, concentrating on routes from the airline's <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> hub to the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, which were the most heavily traveled on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s past, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON>. The pilots union continued to play down <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to hire replacement pilots, saying there simply are n't enough pilots to fill available airline slots, especially at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which are operated by <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` Young pilots know better than to go to work for <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>,'' said Capt <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Saux </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilot and chairman of <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>'s education committee. <PERSON> Saux </PERSON> said in a news release that he and other <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> members have been meeting with pilots from regional airlines and corporations as well as student pilots.
