<HEAD>MCorp to Remain Open Despite Bankruptcy Petition by 3 Creditors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with further background, details on
MCorp, bankruptcy proceedings, editing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' largest banking companies, today announced it would seek protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Code, in response to involuntary bankruptcy petitions filed against it. The troubled bank holding company, which last fall stopped making interest and principal payments on about $ 470 million of debt while it attempted to recapitalize, said three noteholders last week filed a bankruptcy court petition in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> seeking to have <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> involuntarily sold off to pay creditor claims. <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCane </PERSON> said the company learned Friday about the filings for the involuntary Chapter 7 bankruptcy liquidation. `` MCorp deeply regrets that those noteholders ignored our pleas not to take premature and unnecessary action,'' <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer, said in a prepared statement. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> said he hoped the action by a very small number of noteholders seeking to force liquidation of <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> would not disrupt or interfere with discussions between prospective investors and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on terms of a recapitalization plan. Under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law, <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> would be protected from creditor claims while it reorganizes under bankruptcy court supervision and works out a plan to pay debts. <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION>'s Chapter 11 filing would supercede the Chapter 7 petition, which calls for the total sale of the company to satisfy creditors. <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> McCane </PERSON> said the company has not yet indicated when it would ask the bankruptcy court to convert the involuntary liquidation request to a Chapter 11 reorganization case. <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> has 20 days to convert the petitions once the company is served with them. The company's individual MBanks are n't involved, and the filings should not affect the company's business, <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> said. `` We want all of the depositors, customers, employees and suppliers of MBanks to know that our 86 offices will remain open for business as usual,'' <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> said. Since last fall, <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> representatives have met several times with noteholders and urged them not to take action prematurely despite the moratorium on payment of principal and interst on borrowed money while the company proceeded with efforts to recapitalize. The Wall Street Journal identified the three creditors who filed the Chapter 7 petitions as S.N. <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, bond broker that claims to hold $ 2 million principal amount in <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> debentures; and <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eberhardt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, each of whom claims to hold $ 5,000 in debentures. <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> <PERSON> Bader </PERSON>, an attorney for the holders, told the Journal his clients decided to file for Chapter 7 liquidation for fear that <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> would be forced to pump its holding company assets into the failing MBanks, thereby putting the money out of reach of creditors. The Journal quoted analysts as saying <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION>'s move complicates the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to arrange a sale of MCorp. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> had set an April 3 deadline for bids to acquire <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> has the authority to sell or otherwise dispose of insolvent banks once they have been closed by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Comptroller of the Currency, but a bankruptcy filing would make any plan to sell the company subject to a bankruptcy judge's approval. <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> records show that 25 banks owned by <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> posted a $ 213 million fourth-quarter loss and lost $ 903 million in 1988.
