Intermediate price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers gather this week to review a recently-strengthened world oil market and the impact of the cartel's strategy for cutting production to help boost crude prices. Eight ministers of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> were scheduled to begin talks Wednesday at cartel headquarters in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, secretary-general of the 13-nation organization, told reporters last week that the ministers _ members of a monitoring committee _ would review the market and make certain the new accord was working well. The cartel agreed last November on a new quota system limiting each member's output in the first half of this year in an attempt to support a price of $ 18 a barrel. The overall production level was set at 18.5 million barrels a day, well under the actual output at year's end. Many analysts had been skeptical the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries would comply with their quotas, but now say most nations generally have met their targets. `` They've done better adhering to -LRB- their quotas -RRB- than most had expected,'' said <PERSON> Fergus </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, oil analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` Prices have looked amazingly good,'' he said. The average price of a basket of crudes monitored by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> reaching $ 17.50 a barrel last week, up more than $ 5 from late November when the output deal was struck. In <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures trading, the May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, was up 45 cents at $ 20.60 a barrel Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Although Monday's price was inflated by speculation stemming from the closing of the Alaskan pipeline at <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> due to a major offshore oil spill, it still reflected the crude's sharp surge from the two-year low of $ 12.60 reached last Oct. 5. <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said, `` My feeling is that there seems to be a bullish expectation in the market to see a strong price level. So we will enter the second quarter, which is usually a weak quarter, with a stronger demand than had been foreseen.'' Independent producing nations also were expected to curb exports by a total of less than 300,000 barrels daily in the April-June quarter to support <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the world's largest crude producer, said it would join the cuts in the second quarter, when prices generally decline with the onset of warmer weather in oil-importing countries. With the good wintertime results, the ministers also likely will hold initial discussions on production levels for the second half of this year. Those quotas wo n't be set until a full meeting of all <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers June 5 in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s oil minister, told the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> should boost its production ceiling by 1.5 million barrels a day to 20 million barrels in the last six months of the year. He said in an interview published Monday that the cartel's price target should be maintained at $ 18 a barrel. Since the production accord, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> has reported that 12 of the nations complied with the agreement in January and February by curtailing output for the international market. The cartel said the 12 nations pumped 17.4 million barrels of oil a day in February, compared with the daily ceiling of 17.51 million barrels set for those dozen countries. The statement said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> had not reported supply figures in January or February. That country persistently has exceeded its daily quota of 988,000 barrels. Analysts estimate its current production at more than 1.5 million barrels a day. Ministers who form the monitoring committee represent <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. Other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members are <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>.
