<FIRST>r f AM-OilSpillCleanup     03-27 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill Cleanup,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mechanical Means Still Most Popular in Oil Spill Cleanups</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists are experimenting with new uses of chemical agents to aid in the cleanup of oil spills, but mechanical methods such as vacuum pumps, `` skimmer'' boats and absorbant pads are still the most widely used. At the spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, the volume of crude oil in the water is so large _ 10.1 million gallons _ that mechanical means are being supplemented with the use of approved chemicals to disperse some of the oil on the surface. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the tanker that spilled the oil Friday near the port of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, also planned to burn `` fingers'' of the oil slick by igniting them with a laser. Experiments also are being conducted with the use of a chemical agent that, rather than dispersing the oil on the water's surface, causes it to draw together to make it easier to remove with vacuum pumps, said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, a cleanup expert with the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Under the best circumstances, some oil remains in the water after a spill cleanup operation. Wind and wave action emulsify some of it. Some is consumed by bacteria. In an ocean spill, oil on the water's surface can be herded into one area by skimmer boats that use wing-like devices to guide it. Vacuum machines then pump it onto floating barges, which take it ashore in tanks and transfer it to trucks. For oil that has washed ashore or entered shallow-water areas in which skimmer boats can not be used, cleanup crews can use a string of absorbant pads that soak up the crude. A variety of chemicals, usually in liquid form, also can be used to break up sections of the oil slick. Some chemical agents are used to make the oil sink to the bottom, where it poses no direct threat to birds. Burning agents also are used, although questions have been raised about whether the advantages brought by these and other chemical agents outweigh the disadvantages of adding more pollutants to the water or air.
</TEXT>
