<HEAD>Crop Futures Plunge On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices fell sharply Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid forecasts for April showers in the nation's major crop-growing areas. On other markets, orange juice futures surged for the second straight session; energy futures advanced sharply; precious metals were lower and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Wheat futures settled 1 cent to 4 \ cents lower with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.27 \ a bushel; corn was 6 \ cents to 7 -RCB- cents lower with May at $ 2.71 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 9 \ cents to 10 cents lower with May at $ 1.95 \ a bushel; soybeans were 12 cents to 16 cents lower with May at $ The selloff in the grain and soybean markets was widely seen as a reaction to Friday's 6-to-10-day <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> forecast for above-average rainfall March 30-April 3 in most of the central and all of the eastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The winter wheat crop in the central and southern <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> is in need of precipitation and rain also is needed to replenish soil moisture in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, where corn, soybean and oat planting will soon begin. Further selling was attributed to internal market influences and to increasingly bearish expectations for Friday's planted-acreage estimate and quarterly grain stocks report from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` The combination of the threat of precipitation and that very important government report just triggered a lot of liquidation,'' said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a large Chicago-based futures brokerage. A new 6-to-10-day <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> forecast issued after the close called for mostly dry weather in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and parts of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> April 2-6. The soybean market appeared to lead the collapse but oats registered the steepest relative losses. Oats for May and July delivery fell the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a bushel. Frozen concentrated orange juice futures soared the 5-cents-a-pound limit on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on buying linked to reports that some of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s largest orange-juice processors had raised or planned to raise their wholesale prices to $ 1.60 - $ 1.65 a pound from $ 1.50 The price increase may cause a scramble for near-term deliveries but projections for abundant supplies from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> should ensure against supply tightness, said analyst <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Orange juice settled 4.70 to 5 cents higher with May at $ 1.609 a pound Oil futures rose sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid supply-shortage fears linked to the massive oil spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. The spill forced a shutdown of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Port of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, cutting the pipeline output of Alaskan crude oil by more than half. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .13 cent to .42 cent higher with May at $ 20.53 a barrel; heating oil was .86 cent to 1.06 cents higher with April at 57.58 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .35 cent to 1.83 cents higher with April at 59.75 cents a gallon. Gold and silver futures fell on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting a continued easing of inflation fears. Gold settled $ 1.70 to $ 2.10 lower with April at $ 391.60 a troy ounce; silver was 5.7 cents to 6 cents lower with May at $ 6.003 a troy ounce. Cattle futures finished mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, led by a surge of speculative and commercial buying in the feeder cattle market amid indications strong consumer demand. Pork futures ended the day lower with most of the selling stemming from Friday's <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> cold-storage report, which showed a record number of pork bellies in cold storage for the fourth consecutive month. Live cattle settled .25 cent lower to .35 cent higher with April at 78.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .28 cent to 1.10 cents higher with April at 81.97 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .43 cent lower with April at 42.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .18 cent to .98 cent lower with May at 37.17 cents a pound.
