<HEAD>Exxon May Pay Up Willingly To Avoid Damaging Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is likely to pay willingly for the cleanup of the Alaskan oil spill to avoid controversy that could hurt its opportunity to explore for oil in an arctic wildlife refuge, oil analysts said Monday. Exxon is so big that even if it had to pay $ 100 million out of its own coffers for the cleanup its earnings would be lowered by only a nickel a share, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Knuettel </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A bigger priority for the company is winning congressional approval for oil companies to explore in the pristine <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> in northeastern <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Knuettel </PERSON> said The oil spill from the tanker <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> has slowed momentum for the authorization, which passed a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee earlier this month, aides to senators on both sides of the issue said Monday. `` They'd want to handle this as quickly and efficiently as possible'' to limit the damage to its image, <PERSON> Knuettel </PERSON> said. `` This obviously is a setback.'' The Exxon Valdez, carrying 1.2 million barrels of North Slope crude oil, ran onto a reef 25 miles from port early Friday. Estimates put the spill at 240,000 barrels of oil, or about 10.1 million gallons, making it the biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spill on record. Reflecting investors' lack of concern about the spill, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s stock closed unchanged at $ 44.50 a share in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading A long delay in resumption of shipping from the Valdez terminal could hurt <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and other producers if it forced them to cease production temporarily, cutting into their revenue, said <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> <PERSON> Fliakos </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. As for the cleanup itself, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> is liable for the first $ 14 million in damages under terms of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline Authorization Act Up to $ 86 million more could be paid out of a <ORGANIZATION> Trans-Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liability </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> that was funded by tariffs on oil production by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and several smaller <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil producers. However, the administrator of the fund, <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, said Monday that the fund could seek reimbursement from <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> if there was evidence <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> was negligent in the spill. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, who is treasurer of <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> might choose to pay the full costs up front if it wanted to avoid a controversy with the fund over possible negligence. He said he had not heard from Exxon on the matter. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> is a party to two insurance-related agreements, the Tanker Owners Voluntary Agreement Concerning Liability for Oil Pollution and the Contract Regarding A Supplement To Tanker Liability for Oil Pollution. But <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> failed to provide information by late Monday on how those agreements could diminish the cost to Exxon of the cleanup. <PERSON> Knuettel </PERSON> said he did not know if <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s admission that an unlicensed third mate was at the helm of the tanker at the time of the crash could affect its ability to collect on the insurance.
