<HEAD>Motorola Moves Legal Action Against Hitachi to Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has dropped a federal patent-infringement lawsuit filed here against <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, but has filed a virtually identical lawsuit in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, officials of the two companies said Monday. The lawsuit filed in January in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> was engaging in unfair competition with its new H-8 microprocessor. `` <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> does not know why <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> no longer wishes to pursue its claims in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the site of <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION>'s national headquarters,'' said a statement issued by Tokyo-based <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Tarrytown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, home of its <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. `` <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> believes <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> remains the proper place for these lawsuits and it will resist <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION>'s tactical maneuvers to avoid the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> courts.'' But spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Sengstock </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in suburban <LOCATION> Schaumburg </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview that <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> has two plants in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> that make the microprocessors involved in the lawsuit. He said the `` procedural move'' to <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> `` focuses the matter -LRB- to -RRB- the center of our ... microprocessor activity and the site of all the documents, evidence and witnesses.'' <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> also has filed a lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> court, alleging that the <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> 68HC11 microcontroller infringes on a <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> patent. <PERSON> Sengstock </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> is seeking to have the cases combined in the federal court in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> has said that the alleged unfair competition began shortly after <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> granted a patent license to <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> for certain <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> microprocessors in May 1986. The company said the <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> H-8 microprocessor series infringes on at least four <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> patents. <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> has denied any wrongdoing. <PERSON> Sengstock </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> would seek an injunction to stop distribution of the disputed <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> microprocessors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The lawsuit also seeks unspecified damages, he said. Microprocessors are digital electronic devices that perform control and arithmetic functions in a computer. They often contain hundreds of thousands of microscopic transistors on silicon chips about a quarter-inch square.
