<HEAD>Barry Minkow Gets 25 Years In ZZZZ Best Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Minkow quotes, more quotes
from judge, details on sentence, other details, tighten; picks up 15th
graf, ``The government ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who once was hailed as a financial whiz kid, was sentenced to 25 years in prison and ordered to pay $ 26 million restitution for fraud by a judge who called him a charismatic liar. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dickran </PERSON> <PERSON> Tevrizian </PERSON> handed <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, 23, the maximum penalty sought by the government. `` You're dangerous,'' <PERSON> Tevrizian </PERSON> told the 23-year-old <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, `` because you have this gift of gab, this ability to communicate ... -LRB- and -RRB- you do n't have a conscience.'' <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who founded the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> carpet cleaning company, was convicted of 57 counts of securities, credit card and mail fraud on Dec. 14. The government's sentencing memorandum described <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> as a remorseless liar and thief whose schemes cost victims more than $ 100 million. In arguments during Monday's hearing, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Asperger </PERSON> said <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> would probably serve only a third of any sentence imposed. In pleading for a lenient sentence, <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> compared himself to former financier <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who is serving a three-year prison sentence for his role in the Wall Street insider trading scandal. `` This is a great day for this country,'' said <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, clad in blue prison-issue shirt and pants. `` This is a great day for justice. This is how <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> works.'' He commended the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys who prosecuted him, saying, `` They got the right guy. They got the guilty guy. `` I see victims here today,'' he said, turning toward the audience. `` I can only say to them how sorry I am, and I'm going to get what I've got coming, every bit of it.'' But the judge was unmoved by <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s plea or a similar one by defense attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenner </PERSON>, who asked for a sentence of eight to 10 years and psychological counseling for his client. `` That would be a joke,'' snapped <PERSON> Tevrizian </PERSON>. `` Here is someone who has corrupted the financial system. Here is someone who has lied and cheated. That sentence would be a slap on the wrist.'' After <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s appeal, <PERSON> Tevrizian </PERSON> told him, `` You tell me you're sorry and I think, ` Is he trying to clean my carpet or what? The judge ordered that <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> serve five years probation following his release and that the probation would be conditional on his paying the $ 26 million restitution as well as any back taxes or civil judgments against him. The judge also ordered him to participate in a drug dependency program. <PERSON> Kenner </PERSON> said outside court that he would try to get <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s sentence reduced <PERSON> Tevrizian </PERSON> has sentenced 10 other defendants in the case to terms of a month to eight years. In their sentencing memo, <PERSON> Asperger </PERSON> and Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> carried out a `` five-year crime wave'' that `` amounted to a search-and-destroy mission aimed at the trust and integrity of our financial institutions, securities markets and the public at large.'' But <PERSON> Kenner </PERSON> said in a reply memorandum that the young entrepreneur was a victim himself, browbeaten by mobsters and emotionally damaged by a `` dysfunctional family'' characterzied by `` physical abuse, emotional neglect, embarassment, secrecy, lying and mental disorders galore.'' `` The true story of <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> is a young man almost constantly in debt, struggling to prove that he will not become the failure depicted by his father,'' <PERSON> Kenner </PERSON> said. `` Look closely and you will see the picture of a compulsive debtor.'' <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who launched ZZZZ Best at age 16 in his parents' garage, has insisted he was a captive of mobsters who took over his company and forced him to commit fraud. The government claimed he was a shrewd con man who convinced Wall Street investors and TV talk show hosts that he was a teen-age genius. The collapse of ZZZZ Best rocked the volatile <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> money markets and exposed the vulnerability of major securities firms and banks, which bought <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s sales pitch and committed millions to his company. At the center of <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s confidence scheme was a claim that ZZZZ Best was making a fortune restoring water - and fire-damaged buildings Investors were given badges and hard hats and taken on tours of alleged restoration projects in abandoned buildings with which ZZZZ Best had no connection. `` The magnitude and seriousness of defendant <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>'s criminal conduct, coupled with his level of sophistication and ability to manipulate both his cohorts and victims clearly place him among the most significant white-collar criminals ever prosecuted on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>,'' the prosecutors said.
